{"type":"text","timestamp":1778671868663,"sessionID":"ses_1dee5ae94ffewqreCQIqOErIr6","part":{"id":"prt_e211ada2100197GxhXOih4SFLr","messageID":"msg_e211a7c79001iUhEWHvX7NVVfh","sessionID":"ses_1dee5ae94ffewqreCQIqOErIr6","type":"text","text":"Prior micro-opt history favors small datapath/routing reductions and penalizes new prediction/control metadata. The strongest remaining low-risk angle is explicit EX-stage adder sharing for `pc+imm` and `pc+4`, reducing duplicate branch/jump/return-address adders without changing CPI or interfaces.","time":{"start":1778671868449,"end":1778671868662},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0dd893e4d4c53a2b016a0460fc55dc819abce07df17dac70e7","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778671885300,"sessionID":"ses_1dee5ae94ffewqreCQIqOErIr6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_X6QJHreXMjFVgwbEpx9TdNSL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Share EX PC adders\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent micro-opt results show this core is Fmax-sensitive and benefits most\n+  from removing redundant routing or datapath work without adding predictor or\n+  control metadata. The EX stage currently expresses the same PC additions in\n+  several places: branch target, JAL target, JAL/JALR link value, and default\n+  pc_next each independently use `in.pc + in.imm` or `in.pc + 32'd4`. Even if\n+  synthesis shares some logic, making the sharing explicit should reduce adder\n+  duplication, mux input depth, and routing pressure in the branch/jump EX cone.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv to compute shared `pc_plus4` and `pc_imm_sum` wires\n+  once, then feed branch_target, non-JALR jump_target, JAL/JALR rd writeback,\n+  and pc_next from those wires. Keep the existing JALR rs1+imm calculation,\n+  misalignment trap behavior, redirect timing, MDU behavior, RVFI pc_wdata\n+  reporting, and nret=1 top-level interface unchanged.\n+\n+  This is a pure micro-optimization: CoreMark CPI should remain identical, but\n+  median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by trimming redundant 32-bit adders and\n+  simplifying the hot EX redirect/writeback muxing. The risk is low because it\n+  does not alter pipeline state, hazard policy, memory ordering, or decoder\n+  legality.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compute shared pc_plus4 and pc_imm_sum wires in EX and reuse them for branch targets, JAL targets, link writeback, and pc_next.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Share EX PC adders\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent micro-opt results show this core is Fmax-sensitive and benefits most\n+  from removing redundant routing or datapath work without adding predictor or\n+  control metadata. The EX stage currently expresses the same PC additions in\n+  several places: branch target, JAL target, JAL/JALR link value, and default\n+  pc_next each independently use `in.pc + in.imm` or `in.pc + 32'd4`. Even if\n+  synthesis shares some logic, making the sharing explicit should reduce adder\n+  duplication, mux input depth, and routing pressure in the branch/jump EX cone.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv to compute shared `pc_plus4` and `pc_imm_sum` wires\n+  once, then feed branch_target, non-JALR jump_target, JAL/JALR rd writeback,\n+  and pc_next from those wires. Keep the existing JALR rs1+imm calculation,\n+  misalignment trap behavior, redirect timing, MDU behavior, RVFI pc_wdata\n+  reporting, and nret=1 top-level interface unchanged.\n+\n+  This is a pure micro-optimization: CoreMark CPI should remain identical, but\n+  median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by trimming redundant 32-bit adders and\n+  simplifying the hot EX redirect/writeback muxing. The risk is low because it\n+  does not alter pipeline state, hazard policy, memory ordering, or decoder\n+  legality.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compute shared pc_plus4 and pc_imm_sum wires in EX and reuse them for branch targets, JAL targets, link writeback, and pc_next.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Share EX PC adders\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent micro-opt results show this core is Fmax-sensitive and benefits most\n+  from removing redundant routing or datapath work without adding predictor or\n+  control metadata. The EX stage currently expresses the same PC additions in\n+  several places: branch target, JAL target, JAL/JALR link value, and default\n+  pc_next each independently use `in.pc + in.imm` or `in.pc + 32'd4`. Even if\n+  synthesis shares some logic, making the sharing explicit should reduce adder\n+  duplication, mux input depth, and routing pressure in the branch/jump EX cone.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv to compute shared `pc_plus4` and `pc_imm_sum` wires\n+  once, then feed branch_target, non-JALR jump_target, JAL/JALR rd writeback,\n+  and pc_next from those wires. Keep the existing JALR rs1+imm calculation,\n+  misalignment trap behavior, redirect timing, MDU behavior, RVFI pc_wdata\n+  reporting, and nret=1 top-level interface unchanged.\n+\n+  This is a pure micro-optimization: CoreMark CPI should remain identical, but\n+  median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by trimming redundant 32-bit adders and\n+  simplifying the hot EX redirect/writeback muxing. The risk is low because it\n+  does not alter pipeline state, hazard policy, memory ordering, or decoder\n+  legality.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compute shared pc_plus4 and pc_imm_sum wires in EX and reuse them for branch targets, JAL targets, link writeback, and pc_next.\"\n","additions":29,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778671885286,"end":1778671885295}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0dd893e4d4c53a2b016a0460fc8a74819aa282b41a4cfeb7ed"}},"id":"prt_e211adaf7001ZJfG2Gs6CVRbo4","sessionID":"ses_1dee5ae94ffewqreCQIqOErIr6","messageID":"msg_e211a7c79001iUhEWHvX7NVVfh"}}
