y ordering, or decoder\n23:   legality.\n24: expected_impact:\n25:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n26:   confidence: medium\n27: changes:\n28:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n29:     description: \"Compute shared pc_plus4 and pc_imm_sum wires in EX and reuse them for branch targets, JAL targets, link writeback, and pc_next.\"\n\n(End of file - total 29 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\ntitle: \"Share EX PC adders\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  Recent micro-opt results show this core is Fmax-sensitive and benefits most\n  from removing redundant routing or datapath work without adding predictor or\n  control metadata. The EX stage currently expresses the same PC additions in\n  several places: branch target, JAL target, JAL/JALR link value, and default\n  pc_next each independently use `in.pc + in.imm` or `in.pc + 32'd4`. Even if\n  synthesis shares some logic, making the sharing explicit should reduce adder\n  duplication, mux input depth, and routing pressure in the branch/jump EX cone.\nhypothesis: |\n  Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv to compute shared `pc_plus4` and `pc_imm_sum` wires\n  once, then feed branch_target, non-JALR jump_target, JAL/JALR rd writeback,\n  and pc_next from those wires. Keep the existing JALR rs1+imm calculation,\n  misalignment trap behavior, redirect timing, MDU behavior, RVFI pc_wdata\n  reporting, and nret=1 top-level interface unchanged.\n\n  This is a pure micro-optimization: CoreMark CPI should remain identical, but\n  median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by trimming redundant 32-bit adders and","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r10s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778671891064,"end":1778671891075}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_084663c8dc3d7da1016a0461111fc4819b88788445fbff0ceb"}},"id":"prt_e211b2b7a0017XrUbmvBvMGCN9","sessionID":"ses_1dee5ae94ffewqreCQIqOErIr6","messageID":"msg_e211b1c78001irr6smf2M8uZxR"}}
