{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778673595723,"sessionID":"ses_1decbe565ffeNuoIzkEVPLZogL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_kCOZgEiXqBZvQcXbvKAjtfLA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Decode store byte masks\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent bench results show that this core is dominated by Tang Nano 20K Fmax\n+  and routing pressure, while predictor, load-bypass, and control-repacking\n+  changes usually add more logic than CoreMark can recover. One remaining\n+  small combinational cone is the MEM-stage byte-lane mask generation, which\n+  currently uses variable shifts for byte and halfword accesses even though\n+  the mask set is only four fixed byte cases and two fixed halfword cases.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the MEM-stage `4'b0001 << addr[1:0]` and `4'b0011 << addr[1:0]`\n+  byte-mask expressions with explicit fixed-mask decoding from `alu_result[1:0]`.\n+  For halfword accesses, use only `addr[1]` because misaligned halfword cases\n+  are already trapped and never drive a real dmem write mask or RVFI memory\n+  mask. This keeps the memory protocol, misalignment trap behavior, store\n+  buffer semantics, RVFI aligned-memory reporting, and nret=1 interface\n+  unchanged while giving synthesis a smaller mux/decode cone in MEM.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace variable-shift byte_mask generation with explicit fixed byte/halfword mask decoding while preserving misalignment gating.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,24 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Decode store byte masks\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent bench results show that this core is dominated by Tang Nano 20K Fmax\n+  and routing pressure, while predictor, load-bypass, and control-repacking\n+  changes usually add more logic than CoreMark can recover. One remaining\n+  small combinational cone is the MEM-stage byte-lane mask generation, which\n+  currently uses variable shifts for byte and halfword accesses even though\n+  the mask set is only four fixed byte cases and two fixed halfword cases.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the MEM-stage `4'b0001 << addr[1:0]` and `4'b0011 << addr[1:0]`\n+  byte-mask expressions with explicit fixed-mask decoding from `alu_result[1:0]`.\n+  For halfword accesses, use only `addr[1]` because misaligned halfword cases\n+  are already trapped and never drive a real dmem write mask or RVFI memory\n+  mask. This keeps the memory protocol, misalignment trap behavior, store\n+  buffer semantics, RVFI aligned-memory reporting, and nret=1 interface\n+  unchanged while giving synthesis a smaller mux/decode cone in MEM.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace variable-shift byte_mask generation with explicit fixed byte/halfword mask decoding while preserving misalignment gating.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experim