{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778676428720,"sessionID":"ses_1dea052f7ffeSpc7FD0NlU0Po7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_MkrAVsHFBzrbKbhXQHibgjW5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r15s0\n+title: Direct forwarding hit controls\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core is timing-sensitive, and the only recent wins\n+  came from reducing hot-path routing without changing pipeline behavior.\n+  The EX operand path still builds two 2-bit forwarding select values in\n+  forward_unit, routes them into ex_stage, and decodes them back into mux\n+  choices for rs1 and rs2. That small encoder/decode layer sits directly on\n+  the forwarding-to-ALU/branch compare path that CoreMark exercises heavily.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the 2-bit forwarding select interface with direct one-hot producer\n+  hit controls for each operand, for example fwd_rs1_exmem, fwd_rs1_memwb,\n+  fwd_rs2_exmem, and fwd_rs2_memwb. Keep the existing priority of EX/MEM over\n+  MEM/WB inside the EX operand mux, and preserve the current rd!=0 checks and\n+  producer sidebands so this does not repeat the failed x0 pre-gating attempt.\n+\n+  This is a pure micro-optimization: it does not change CPI, load-use stalls,\n+  memory ordering, MDU behavior, RVFI reporting, or the nret=1 IO contract.\n+  The expected benefit is a modest median Fmax improvement by removing the\n+  forwarding select encoder, narrowing two routed control buses, and giving\n+  synthesis simpler direct mux-enable equations in the hot EX stage.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Change the forwarding unit outputs from two 2-bit select buses to direct EX/MEM and MEM/WB hit signals per source operand, preserving EX/MEM priority and local rd!=0 checks.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume direct forwarding hit controls in the rs1/rs2 muxes instead of decoding 2-bit select values, with identical operand priority and fallback behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update the top-level forwarding wires and module connections to carry the direct hit controls between forward_unit and ex_stage.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r15s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,32 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r15s0\n+title: Direct forwarding hit controls\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best bench core is timing-sensitive, and the only recent wins\n+  came from reducing hot-path routing without changing pipeline behavior.\n+  The EX operand path still builds two 2-bit forwarding select values in\n+  forward_unit, routes them into ex_stage, and decodes them back into mux\n+  choices for rs1 and rs2. That small encoder/decode layer sits directly on\n+  the forwarding-to-ALU/branch compare path that CoreMark exercises heavily.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the 2-bit forwarding select interface with direct one-hot producer\n+  hit controls for each operand, for example fwd_rs1_exmem, fwd_rs1_memwb,\n+  fwd_rs2_exmem, and fwd_rs2_memwb. Keep the existing priority of EX/MEM over\n+  MEM/WB inside the EX operand mux, and preserve the current rd!=0 checks and\n+  producer sidebands so 