{"type":"text","timestamp":1778664190881,"sessionID":"ses_1df5b27f1ffeuoUlLaB70tUYXZ","part":{"id":"prt_e20a5b0e2002b2ttSWZbvg5925","messageID":"msg_e20a52a8e001kd1Csvy24ukWr0","sessionID":"ses_1df5b27f1ffeuoUlLaB70tUYXZ","type":"text","text":"The prior successful micro-opts were metadata/reset pruning, while predictor/front-end changes regressed. I’m going to write a single micro-opt hypothesis that narrows downstream control bundles instead of adding new behavior.","time":{"start":1778664190178,"end":1778664190880},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0c13533b431bd427016a0442fe0320819a880beaa57274bd53","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778664221959,"sessionID":"ses_1df5b27f1ffeuoUlLaB70tUYXZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_oE7FaJB7tfpbbSN4IIGGxM06","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Narrow downstream control bundles\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best prior bench improvements came from removing reset fanout and dead\n+  pipeline metadata, while recent front-end and predictor changes lost Fmax.\n+  The current RTL still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and\n+  MEM/WB even though most of those bits are only needed in EX. On a small FPGA\n+  this wastes flip-flops, mux inputs, and routing on every pipeline stage.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the monolithic ctrl_t payload into narrower downstream control records:\n+  keep the existing full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, replace EX/MEM control with\n+  just the memory/writeback/trap bits consumed by MEM and hazard logic, and\n+  replace MEM/WB control with only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. This\n+  preserves decode legality, branch/jump resolution, memory masks, RVFI fields,\n+  and the nret=1 interface while pruning unused ALU, branch, jump, and immediate\n+  select metadata after EX.\n+\n+  CPI should be unchanged because no behavior or timing protocol changes. The\n+  expected gain is a modest Fmax lift from narrower EX/MEM and MEM/WB registers,\n+  lower control fanout, and simpler downstream muxing, following the same proven\n+  direction as the earlier dead-metadata pruning win without repeating the\n+  mem_to_reg fanout mistake.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add narrow ex_mem_ctrl_t and mem_wb_ctrl_t records, then change ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t to use them instead of carrying full ctrl_t downstream.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Pack only the memory width/sign, memory enable, writeback select, reg_write, and trap bits into the EX/MEM control record.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrower EX/MEM control record, generate the narrower MEM/WB control record after misalignment trap handling, and keep RVFI memory fields unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update hazard and RVFI references to the narrowed downstream control fields without changing top-level ports or retirement order.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the narrowed MEM/WB writeback control fields for the existing write-enable and load-result select mux.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,37 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Narrow downstream control bundles\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best prior bench improvements came from removing reset fanout and dead\n+  pipeline metadata, while recent front-end and predictor changes lost Fmax.\n+  The current RTL still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and\n+  MEM/WB even though most of those bits are only needed in EX. On a small FPGA\n+  this wastes flip-flops, mux inputs, and routing on every pipeline stage.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split the monolithic ctrl_t payload into narrower downstream control records:\n+  keep the existing full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, replace EX/MEM control with\n+  just the memory/writeback/trap bits consumed by MEM and hazard logic, and\n+  replace MEM/WB control with only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. This\n+  preserves decode legality, branch/jump resolution, memory masks, RVFI fields,\n+  and the nret=1 interface while pruning unused ALU, branch, jump, and immediate\n+  select metadata after EX.\n+\n+  CPI should be unchanged because no behavior or timing protocol changes. The\n+  expected gain is a modest Fmax lift from narrower EX/MEM and MEM/WB registers,\n+  lower control fanout, and simpler downstream muxing, following the same proven\n+  direction as the earlier dead-metadata pruning win without repeating the\n+  mem_to_reg fanout mistake.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add narrow ex_mem_ctrl_t and mem_wb_ctrl_t records, then change ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t to use them instead of carrying full ctrl_t downstream.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Pack only the memory width/sign, memory enable, writeback select, reg_write, and trap bits into the EX/MEM control record.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrower EX/MEM control record, generate the narrower MEM/WB control record after misalignment trap handling, and keep RVFI memory fields unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Update hazard and RVFI references to the narrowed downstream control fields without changing top-level ports or retirement order.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Use the narrowed MEM/WB writeback control fields for the existing write-enable and load-result select mux.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiment