{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778669647993,"sessionID":"ses_1df085168ffeSfLP7eT50ann93","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_hBhmFu64H1E7z1pThUn0lkOi","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\n+title: \"Iterative divider MDU\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current MDU moved RV32M work out of the common ALU path, but the real\n+  hardware branch still uses SystemVerilog divide and remainder operators to\n+  compute DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally at start. Even with a 34-cycle\n+  latency counter, synthesis must build large divider/modulo cones that can\n+  consume LUTs and constrain placement on Tang Nano 20K. CoreMark's timed hot\n+  path is dominated by RV32I plus occasional multiplies, so rare division\n+  latency is a better tradeoff than carrying a wide combinational divider.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in rtl/mdu.sv with a\n+  small iterative restoring divider that reuses one subtract/compare step per\n+  cycle and produces both quotient and remainder after roughly 32 cycles. Keep\n+  the existing interface, ALTOPS formulas, multiply results, divide-by-zero,\n+  signed overflow, and RV32M result semantics unchanged. This should reduce\n+  divider LUT/routing pressure and may improve median Fmax while leaving the\n+  common RV32I pipeline, memory protocol, RVFI retirement, and nret=1 IO\n+  untouched. The CPI risk is limited because CoreMark rarely executes integer\n+  division in the measured loop, and the old advertised divide latency was\n+  already multicycle.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mdu.sv\n+    description: \"Replace synthesized combinational DIV/REM operators with an iterative divider state machine while preserving RV32M edge cases and ALTOPS behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\n+title: \"Iterative divider MDU\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current MDU moved RV32M work out of the common ALU path, but the real\n+  hardware branch still uses SystemVerilog divide and remainder operators to\n+  compute DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally at start. Even with a 34-cycle\n+  latency counter, synthesis must build large divider/modulo cones that can\n+  consume LUTs and constrain placement on Tang Nano 20K. CoreMark's timed hot\n+  path is dominated by RV32I plus occasional multiplies, so rare division\n+  latency is a better tradeoff than carrying a wide combinational divider.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in rtl/mdu.sv with a\n+  small iterative restoring divider that reuses one subtract/compare step per\n+  cycle and produces both quotient and remainder after roughly 32 cycles. Keep\n+  the existing interface, ALTOPS formulas, multiply results, divide-by-zero,\n+  signed overflow, and RV32M result semantics unchanged. This should reduce\n+  divider LUT/routing pressure and may improve median Fmax while leaving the\n+  common RV32I pipeline, memory protocol, RVFI retirement, and nret=1 IO\n+  untouched. The CPI risk is limited because CoreMark rarely executes integer\n+  division in the measured 