{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778672683732,"sessionID":"ses_1deda830effepLLiklnjw5dkNk","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_UOOZ71A7JXxmMuMzJdMKjskN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\n2: title: \"Forward loads from store buffer\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current best structural win is the one-entry posted store buffer, which\n6:   lets isolated stores retire while a stalled dmem write drains. Its remaining\n7:   conservative rule is that every younger memory operation stalls behind any\n8:   buffered store, even when the younger load reads bytes wholly covered by that\n9:   pending store. CoreMark stack and struct traffic can contain store-then-load\n10:   pairs where random dmem backpressure currently turns a safe forwarding case\n11:   into a full pipeline stall.\n12: hypothesis: |\n13:   Add store-buffer load forwarding inside the existing MEM-stage decoupling\n14:   structure. When the posted store buffer is full and the instruction in EX/MEM\n15:   is a valid, aligned load to the same word with a byte mask fully covered by\n16:   the buffered store mask, synthesize the load word from the buffered replicated\n17:   store data, let the load retire normally, and do not assert a dmem read for\n18:   that forwarded access. Keep all nonmatching, partially covered, misaligned,\n19:   and store-following-memory cases stalled behind the buffer exactly as today.\n20: \n21:   This preserves precise in-order retirement, RVFI memory reporting, and the\n22:   nret=1 top-level contract while improving the useful decoupling of the proven\n23:   one-entry store buffer. The change stays entirely in the back end, avoiding\n24:   the front-end replay and prediction paths that repeatedly regressed.\n25: expected_impact:\n26:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n27:   confidence: medium\n28: changes:\n29:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n30:     description: \"Detect same-word store-buffer hits for aligned loads whose requested byte mask is fully covered, return buffered data as load data, suppress dmem_ren for forwarded loads, and report correct RVFI rdata/rmask.\"\n31:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n32:     description: \"Allow a current EX/MEM load to proceed while the posted store buffer is full only when mem_stage reports that the load can be fully forwarded from the buffer.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n34:     description: \"Wire the store-buffer load-forwarding qualification from mem_stage into hazard_unit without changing the nret=1 IO shape.\"\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\ntitle: \"Forward loads from store buffer\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current best structural win is the one-entry posted store buffer, which\n  lets isolated stores retire while a stalled dmem write drains. Its remaining\n  conservative rule is that every younger memory operation stalls behind any\n  buffered store, even when the younger load reads bytes wholly covered by that\n  pending store. CoreMark stack and struct traffic can contain store-then-load\n  pairs where random dmem backpressure currently turns a safe forwarding case\n  into a full pipeline stall.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add store-buffer load forwarding inside the existing MEM-stage decoupling\n  structure. When the posted store buffer is full and the instruction in EX/MEM\n  is a valid, aligned load to the same word with a byte mask fully covered by\n  the buffered store mask, synthesize the load word from the buffered replicated\n  store data, let the load retire normally, and do not assert a dmem read for\n  that forwarded access. Keep all nonmatching, partially covered, misaligned,\n  and store-following-memory cases stalled behind the buffer exactly as today.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r11s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778672683728,"end":1778672683731}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02ebd0cd27b78368016a0464293544819ab4061557d4452950"}},"id":"prt_e2127415a0010v15KuaaFdnJ53","sessionID":"ses_1deda830effepLLiklnjw5dkNk","messageID":"msg_e2127215f001l2rpT9vFZooia0"}}
