{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778674551036,"sessionID":"ses_1debd252affekhMCtzPmA4LuIT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_jqL3aS0qMk4v7MWO0eueIuEd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Split writeback commit sideband\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\n+\n+  The MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add an explicit narrow writeback commit sideband alongside the existing MEM/WB RVFI record. The sideband should carry only valid, reg_write, rd, and the already-registered wb_data from mem_stage to wb_stage, the regfile write port, and the MEM/WB forwarding sideband. Keep the full mem_wb_t record for RVFI retirement and memory reporting only, with the same hold-on-dmem-stall semantics that prevent double retirement while preserving old forwarding data.\n+\n+  This is a structural isolation/retiming change rather than a new predictor or queue. It should preserve instruction count, RVFI order, traps, memory behavior, and the nret=1 top-level interface while giving synthesis a smaller, more local writeback cone. The expected gain is a modest Fmax lift similar in spirit to the recent forwarding sideband improvement, with low CPI risk because no stall or retirement policy changes.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a narrow writeback commit sideband type carrying only valid, reg_write, rd, and wb_data while leaving mem_wb_t available for RVFI metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive the new registered commit sideband in parallel with the existing MEM/WB RVFI record, preserving dmem hold behavior and stored forwarding data across stalls.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the narrow commit sideband from mem_stage to wb_stage and to the MEM/WB forwarding sideband so hot writeback logic no longer reads the wide RVFI bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrow commit sideband instead of the full MEM/WB record for regfile write enable, destination, and data.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Split writeback commit sideband\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\n+\n+  The MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add an explicit narrow writeback commit sideband alongside the existing MEM/WB RVFI record. The sideband should carry only valid, reg_write, rd, and the already-registered wb_data from mem_stage to wb_stage, the regfile write port, and the MEM/WB forwarding sideband. Keep the full mem_wb_t record for RVFI retirement and memory reporting only, with the same hold-on-dmem-stall semantics that prevent double retirement while preserving old forwarding data.\n+\n+  This is a structural isolation/retiming change rather than a new predictor or queue. It should preserve instruction count, RVFI order, traps, memory behavior, and the nret=1 top-level interface while giving synthesis a smaller, more local writeback cone. The expected gain is a modest Fmax lift similar in spirit to the recent forwarding sideband improvement, with low CPI risk because no stall or retirement policy changes.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a narrow writeback commit sideband type carrying only valid, reg_write, rd, and wb_data while leaving mem_wb_t available for RVFI metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive the new registered commit sideband in parallel with the existing MEM/WB RVFI record, preserving dmem hold behavior and stored forwarding data across stalls.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the narrow commit sideband from mem_stage to wb_stage and to the MEM/WB forwarding sideband so hot writeback logic no longer reads the wide RVFI bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrow commit sideband instead of the full MEM/WB record for regfile write enable, destination, and data.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,23 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Split writeback commit sideband\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\n+\n+  The MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add an explicit narrow writeback commit sideband alongside the existing MEM/WB RVFI record. The sideband should carry only valid, reg_write, rd, and the already-registered wb_data from mem_stage to wb_stage, the regfile write port, and the MEM/WB forwarding sideband. Keep the full mem_wb_t record for RVFI retirement and memory reporting only, with the same hold-on-dmem-stall semantics that prevent double retirement while preserving old forwarding data.\n+\n+  This is a structural isolation/retiming change rather than a new predictor or queue. It should preserve instruction count, RVFI order, traps, memory behavior, and the nret=1 top-level interface while giving synthesis a smaller, more local writeback cone. The expected gain is a modest Fmax lift similar in spirit to the recent forwarding sideband improvement, with low CPI risk because no stall or retirement policy changes.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a narrow writeback commit sideband type carrying only valid, reg_write, rd, and wb_data while leaving mem_wb_t available for RVFI metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Drive the new registered commit sideband in parallel with the existing MEM/WB RVFI record, preserving dmem hold behavior and stored forwarding data across stalls.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the narrow commit sideband from mem_stage to wb_stage and to the MEM/WB forwarding sideband so hot writeback logic no longer reads the wide RVFI bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrow commit sideband instead of the full MEM/WB record for regfile write enable, destination, and data.\"\n","additions":23,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778674551027,"end":1778674551034}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03a1aaf4e9f0440c016a046b5f9b24819b81a12f46f230fce0"}},"id":"prt_e21436de1001RUbeSa4o2pcOFl","sessionID":"ses_1debd252affekhMCtzPmA4LuIT","messageID":"msg_e21435a80001CY7DapVUZ1om5Z"}}
