{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778674556775,"sessionID":"ses_1debd252affekhMCtzPmA4LuIT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_r6j4mQlVwQFDjf9fEvibE6JU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n2: title: \"Split writeback commit sideband\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\n6: \n7:   The MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Add an explicit narrow writeback commit sideband alongside the existing MEM/WB RVFI record. The sideband should carry only valid, reg_write, rd, and the already-registered wb_data from mem_stage to wb_stage, the regfile write port, and the MEM/WB forwarding sideband. Keep the full mem_wb_t record for RVFI retirement and memory reporting only, with the same hold-on-dmem-stall semantics that prevent double retirement while preserving old forwarding data.\n10: \n11:   This is a structural isolation/retiming change rather than a new predictor or queue. It should preserve instruction count, RVFI order, traps, memory behavior, and the nret=1 top-level interface while giving synthesis a smaller, more local writeback cone. The expected gain is a modest Fmax lift similar in spirit to the recent forwarding sideband improvement, with low CPI risk because no stall or retirement policy changes.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n17:     description: \"Add a narrow writeback commit sideband type carrying only valid, reg_write, rd, and wb_data while leaving mem_wb_t available for RVFI metadata.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n19:     description: \"Drive the new registered commit sideband in parallel with the existing MEM/WB RVFI record, preserving dmem hold behavior and stored forwarding data across stalls.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n21:     description: \"Wire the narrow commit sideband from mem_stage to wb_stage and to the MEM/WB forwarding sideband so hot writeback logic no longer reads the wide RVFI bundle.\"\n22:   - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n23:     description: \"Consume the narrow commit sideband instead of the full MEM/WB record for regfile write enable, destination, and data.\"\n\n(End of file - total 23 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\ntitle: \"Split writeback commit sideband\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\n\n  The MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add an explicit narrow writeback commit sideband alongside the existing MEM/WB RVFI record. The sideband should carry only valid, reg_write, rd, and the already-registered wb_data from mem_stage to wb_stage, the regfile write port, and the MEM/WB forwarding sideband. Keep the full mem_wb_t record for RVFI retirement and memory reporting only, with the same hold-on-dmem-stall semantics that prevent double retirement while preserving old forwarding data.\n\n  This is a structural isolation/retiming change rather than a new predictor or queue. It should preserve instruction count, RVFI order, traps, memory behavior, and the nret=1 top-level interface while giving synthesis a smaller, more local writeback cone. The expected gain is a modest Fmax lift similar in spirit to the recent forwarding sideband improvement, with low CPI risk because no stall or retirement policy changes.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add a narrow writeback commit sideband type carrying only valid, reg_write, rd, and wb_data while leaving mem_wb_t available for RVFI metadata.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Drive the new registered commit sideband in parallel with the existing MEM/WB RVFI record, preserving dmem hold behavior and stored forwarding data across stalls.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778674556770,"end":1778674556774}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_050a213c54116df4016a046b7b7bfc819a9c984f93e1025122"}},"id":"prt_e2143dac7001smBrpwZ6QeRz3X","sessionID":"ses_1debd252affekhMCtzPmA4LuIT","messageID":"msg_e2143c995001czUMZMPa3WaTRN"}}
