{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778675374628,"sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_aWRPnpIOw2eXC5kMajFAKH80","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: structural|\"category\": \"structural\"|structural|split|stage|pipeline|retim|register|IF/ID|MEM/WB|EX/MEM","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 38 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Remove regfile reset fanout\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a\\nsynchronous for-loop. On FPGA this discourages LUTRAM-style inference for the\\n32x32 storage and adds reset muxing/fanout across a hot, frequently accessed\\nstructure. RV32I does not require integer registers other than x0 to have a\\ndefined reset value, and x0 is already hardwired through read/write gating.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a\\nsynchronous for-loop. On FPGA this discourages LUTRAM-style inference for the\\n32x32 storage and adds reset muxing/fanout across a hot, frequently accessed\\nstructure. RV32I does not require integer registers other than x0 to have a\\ndefined reset value, and x0 is already hardwired through read/write gating.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Change rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears the backing register array.\\nPreserve the existing write-first bypass, x0 read-as-zero behavior, and write\\nsuppression to x0. This should reduce flip-flop/reset routing pressure and may\\nlet synthesis map the register file to distributed RAM or a smaller muxed\\nstructure, improving Fmax with negligible CoreMark CPI risk because compiled C\\ncode initializes live registers before use.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 hardwiring and write-first read bypass semantics.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 hardwiring and write-first read bypass semantics.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 316.22, \"delta_pct\": 11.81, \"vs_baseline\": 11.81, \"fmax_mhz\": 142.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"c...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve branches in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every branch and jump in EX, so each\\ntaken redirect flushes two younger instructions. CoreMark spends many cycles\\nin tight counted loops and function-call-heavy list/state code, making taken\\ncontrol transfers a direct CPI cost. Reducing the redirect penalty by one\\nstage should improve iterations per cycle without changing the nret=1 RVFI\\ncontract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every branch and jump in EX, so each\\ntaken redirect flushes two younger instructions. CoreMark spends many cycles\\nin tight counted loops and function-call-heavy list/state code, making taken\\ncontrol transfers a direct CPI cost. Reducing the redirect penalty by one\\nstage should improve iterations per cycle without changing the nret=1 RVFI\\ncontract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an ID-stage early redirect path for conditional branches, JAL, and JALR\\nwhen their operands are already available from the regfile or safe same-cycle\\nbypasses. The ID stage can compute immediates, branch comparisons, and jump\\ntargets one cycle earlier than EX; when it redirects, IF emits a bubble and\\nID/EX captures a bubble so the control-transfer instruction still retires\\nthrough the normal pipeline with correct RVFI pc_wdata. Cases needing an\\nunavailable producer, especially load-use and EX/MEM load results, fall back\\nto the existing EX resolution path for correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire an early ID redirect signal into IF and hazard control while preserving the existing EX redirect fallback and single-channel RVFI retirement.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute branch and jump targets in ID, compare available operands with WB bypassing, emit an early redirect, and carry the resolved pc_next metadat...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Add tiny BTB and BHT branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always fetches pc+4 and resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken control-flow instruction pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark contains tight loops and repeated call/return style control flow where even a very small FPGA-friendly predictor should learn the hot backedges and reduce bubbles. A predictor is especially attractive under the random instruction-stall workload because it improves useful fetch placement without adding memory-system complexity.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always fetches pc+4 and resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken control-flow instruction pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark contains tight loops and repeated call/return style control flow where even a very small FPGA-friendly predictor should learn the hot backedges and reduce bubbles. A predictor is especially attractive under the random instruction-stall workload because it improves useful fetch placement without adding memory-system complexity.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with 2-bit saturating direction counters in the IF stage. The IF stage predicts taken when the PC tag hits and the BHT counter is weak/strong taken, uses the cached target as next_pc, and carries predicted_pc/predicted_taken metadata down the pipeline. EX compares the actual resolved next PC against the prediction, redirects only on mispredict, and updates the BTB/BHT for branches and jumps. This should preserve correctness through the existing redirect/flush machinery while converting most steady-state CoreMark loop backedges from taken-branch flushes into correctly predicted fetches.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipel...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Qualify load-use source checks\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against both\\nraw source bitfields of the following instruction for every opcode. For many\\nRV32I instructions, one or both of those bitfields are immediate bits or are\\notherwise unused, so a coincidental match with the prior load's rd injects a\\nneedless one-cycle bubble. CoreMark has frequent loads followed by immediate\\narithmetic, address updates, jumps, and upper-immediate instructions where\\navoiding false dependencies should improve iterations per cycle without\\ntouching the proven datapath or memory protocol.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against both\\nraw source bitfields of the following instruction for every opcode. For many\\nRV32I instructions, one or both of those bitfields are immediate bits or are\\notherwise unused, so a coincidental match with the prior load's rd injects a\\nneedless one-cycle bubble. CoreMark has frequent loads followed by immediate\\narithmetic, address updates, jumps, and upper-immediate instructions where\\navoiding false dependencies should improve iterations per cycle without\\ntouching the proven datapath or memory protocol.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Teach the hazard unit which IF/ID operands are actually consumed before\\napplying the load-use comparison. Keep the true load-use stall for branches,\\nstores, R-type operations, JALR, OP-IMM rs1 uses, and real load base-register\\ndependencies, but ignore rs2 for I-type/load/JALR immediates and ignore both\\noperands for LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK. This is a small combinational\\ndecode in the existing hazard path that should remove spurious bubbles while\\npreserving all forwarding, RVFI order, trap, and bus-stall behavior.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"de...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\\nremainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\\nCoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\\nsynthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\\nEX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\\noperations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\\na favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\\nremainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\\nCoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\\nsynthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\\nEX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\\noperations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\\na favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\\nmulticycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\\nfor add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\\nALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\\nhalf of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\\ninto the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\\nstay unchanged.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\\ndivider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should b...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches pc+4 and pays a two-instruction\\nredirect penalty for every taken branch and jump resolved in EX. CoreMark has\\nmany small counted loops where backward conditional branches are taken most\\niterations, plus direct JAL call/loop control transfers with targets fully\\nencoded in the fetched instruction. A tiny static predictor can recover much\\nof that CPI loss with less state and less correctness risk than the previous\\nBTB/BHT attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches pc+4 and pays a two-instruction\\nredirect penalty for every taken branch and jump resolved in EX. CoreMark has\\nmany small counted loops where backward conditional branches are taken most\\niterations, plus direct JAL call/loop control transfers with targets fully\\nencoded in the fetched instruction. A tiny static predictor can recover much\\nof that CPI loss with less state and less correctness risk than the previous\\nBTB/BHT attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add decode-light prediction in IF for direct control flow only: predict JAL\\ntaken to its J-immediate target, predict conditional branches with negative\\nB-immediates taken, and leave forward branches plus JALR as pc+4. Carry the\\npredicted next PC with the instruction through IF/ID and ID/EX. EX still\\ncomputes the authoritative next PC and RVFI pc_wdata, but redirects and\\nflushes only when the predicted next PC differs from the actual next PC.\\nThis keeps the existing retirement semantics intact while eliminating the\\nsteady-state flush on hot backward CoreMark loop branches and direct jumps.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can compare speculation against the resolved next PC without changing RV...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead pipeline metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current post-MDU core is Fmax-sensitive enough that small reductions in\\npipeline register width and hot-stage routing can still move Tang Nano 20K\\nfitness. Several metadata fields are carried after decode/execute but are not\\nconsumed by any later stage or by RVFI: LUI is already represented by\\nalu_op=ALU_LUI plus alu_src, and EX-stage branch_taken/branch_target are only\\nused locally before being redundantly flopped into EX/MEM.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current post-MDU core is Fmax-sensitive enough that small reductions in\\npipeline register width and hot-stage routing can still move Tang Nano 20K\\nfitness. Several metadata fields are carried after decode/execute but are not\\nconsumed by any later stage or by RVFI: LUI is already represented by\\nalu_op=ALU_LUI plus alu_src, and EX-stage branch_taken/branch_target are only\\nused locally before being redundantly flopped into EX/MEM.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove dead metadata from the pipeline bundles and the wiring that feeds it:\\ndrop ctrl_t.is_lui and the decoder/id-stage plumbing for it, and drop\\nex_mem_t.branch_taken plus ex_mem_t.branch_target and their EX-stage register\\nassignments. This should reduce flip-flops, mux inputs, and routing pressure\\nacross ID/EX and EX/MEM without changing instruction semantics, branch\\nredirect timing, memory behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI retirement interface.\\nBecause the change is pure metadata pruning, CPI should be unchanged while\\nmedian Fmax may improve modestly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove unused ctrl_t.is_lui and dead ex_mem_t branch_taken/branch_target fields from the pipeline bundle definitions.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the unused is_lui output and its assignments while preserving LUI legality, ALU_LUI select...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Add one-entry fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\\nthe PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\\nrandom instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\\nthis tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\\ncycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\\nfetched word.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\\nfront-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\\nthe fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\\nit should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\\nthe existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\\nthe PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\\nrandom instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\\nthis tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\\ncycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\\nfetched word.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\\nfront-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\\nthe fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\\nit should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\\nthe existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry IF/ID fetch skid buffer in the front end. When imemReady is\\nhigh but decode is stalled by load-use, dmem backpressure, or an MDU busy\\nperiod, capture the current fetched instruction and PC instead of emitting a\\nbubble or requiring the instruction bus to be ...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny return address predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The previous predictor attempts show that putting branch-immediate decode or\\nBTB/BHT lookup directly on the IF next-PC path can either break RVFI redirect\\nsemantics or lose enough Fmax to erase loop CPI gains. CoreMark still has many\\ncall and return transfers, and returns are expensive in the current core\\nbecause every JALR resolves in EX and flushes two younger instructions.\\n\\nA very small return-address predictor targets only the indirect-control case\\nthat static backward prediction cannot cover, while avoiding a broad branch\\ndirection predictor in the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous predictor attempts show that putting branch-immediate decode or\\nBTB/BHT lookup directly on the IF next-PC path can either break RVFI redirect\\nsemantics or lose enough Fmax to erase loop CPI gains. CoreMark still has many\\ncall and return transfers, and returns are expensive in the current core\\nbecause every JALR resolves in EX and flushes two younger instructions.\\n\\nA very small return-address predictor targets only the indirect-control case\\nthat static backward prediction cannot cover, while avoiding a broad branch\\ndirection predictor in the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2- or 4-entry return-address stack that pushes pc+4 for ordinary direct\\ncalls and predicts JALR returns when the fetched instruction matches the\\nstandard return shape, such as JALR x0, x1, 0 or JALR x0, x5, 0. The IF stage\\nshould keep the normal pc+4 path for all other instructions, so the added\\nlogic is a narrow opcode/funct/rd/rs1/imm equality check plus a small mux to a\\nregistered stack top.\\n\\nCarry predicted-next-PC metadata with the instruction and keep EX as the\\nauthoritative resolver. On mismatch, use the existing redirect/flush path; on\\nmatch, suppress only the unnecessary redirect flush while preserving RVFI\\npc_wdata from E...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Prune load writeback select bit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best bench core is already dominated by FPGA Fmax rather than\\nlarge CPI opportunities, and the recent successful micro-opts both came\\nfrom removing unnecessary reset or pipeline metadata. One remaining control\\nbit, mem_to_reg, is redundant with mem_read: every legal load asserts both,\\nand no non-load instruction should select the loaded-data path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best bench core is already dominated by FPGA Fmax rather than\\nlarge CPI opportunities, and the recent successful micro-opts both came\\nfrom removing unnecessary reset or pipeline metadata. One remaining control\\nbit, mem_to_reg, is redundant with mem_read: every legal load asserts both,\\nand no non-load instruction should select the loaded-data path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove ctrl_t.mem_to_reg from the pipeline control bundle and use mem_read\\ndirectly as the writeback-stage load-result selector. This eliminates one\\ndecoded control bit from the ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB payloads plus its\\ndecoder and ID-stage plumbing, without changing retirement timing, memory\\nbehavior, RVFI fields, or the nret=1 top-level interface. The expected win\\nis modest but low-risk: slightly narrower pipeline registers and less\\nrouting/mux control on a core whose prior Fmax improved from similar\\nmetadata pruning.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the redundant ctrl_t.mem_to_reg field from the shared control bundle definition.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the mem_to_reg output and assignments; keep mem_read, reg_write, legality, and load width/sign controls unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove decoder mem_to_reg wiring and stop populating the eliminated control bit in ID/EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\"...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register the IF ID boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID pipeline register: imem_data, PC,\\ndecode, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and the ID/EX\\ncapture all sit in one cycle. After the successful MDU split and metadata\\npruning, the remaining Tang Nano 20K fitness is likely limited by routing and\\nlong stage boundaries rather than by CoreMark CPI alone.\\n\\nPrior structural and predictor attempts that added front-end speculation or\\nreplay state regressed because they put new work on the fetch next-PC path.\\nA plain IF/ID register is a narrower structural retiming that does not try to\\npredict control flow; it simply cuts the fetch-to-decode path and lets the PC\\nand instruction memory interface settle before decode consumes the word.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID pipeline register: imem_data, PC,\\ndecode, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and the ID/EX\\ncapture all sit in one cycle. After the successful MDU split and metadata\\npruning, the remaining Tang Nano 20K fitness is likely limited by routing and\\nlong stage boundaries rather than by CoreMark CPI alone.\\n\\nPrior structural and predictor attempts that added front-end speculation or\\nreplay state regressed because they put new work on the fetch next-PC path.\\nA plain IF/ID register is a narrower structural retiming that does not try to\\npredict control flow; it simply cuts the fetch-to-decode path and lets the PC\\nand instruction memory interface settle before decode consumes the word.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the current combinational IF/ID bundle into a registered pipeline\\nboundary owned by if_stage. The IF stage should capture pc, instr, and valid\\nwhen imemReady is high and decode can advance; hold the registered bundle\\nduring load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls; and flush it on redirects or invalid\\ninstruction-fetch cycles....\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry loop target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts show that broad IF-stage decode, BTB/BHT state, and return-shape logic can cost more Tang Nano 20K Fmax than they recover in CPI. CoreMark still pays a two-instruction redirect penalty on hot taken loop backedges, so the best remaining predictor angle is one that learns those targets without re-decoding immediates on the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts show that broad IF-stage decode, BTB/BHT state, and return-shape logic can cost more Tang Nano 20K Fmax than they recover in CPI. CoreMark still pays a two-instruction redirect penalty on hot taken loop backedges, so the best remaining predictor angle is one that learns those targets without re-decoding immediates on the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry last-taken control-flow target predictor. EX remains the authoritative branch/jump resolver and, whenever a valid taken branch or direct jump retires through the existing redirect path, records the resolved PC and target in two small registers. IF predicts only when the current PC equals that registered PC, using the registered target as next_pc; all other fetches stay on the current pc+4 path.\\n\\nCarry predicted-next-PC metadata with each instruction so EX can compare the actual resolved next PC against the predicted one and only flush on mismatch. This targets steady-state counted loops with much less fetch-path logic than the prior static predictor or BTB/BHT, while preserving RVFI pc_wdata/order semantics and using the existing redirect machinery for recovery.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate speculation without changing the nret=1 RVFI interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"de...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Narrow downstream control bundles\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The best prior bench improvements came from removing reset fanout and dead\\npipeline metadata, while recent front-end and predictor changes lost Fmax.\\nThe current RTL still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and\\nMEM/WB even though most of those bits are only needed in EX. On a small FPGA\\nthis wastes flip-flops, mux inputs, and routing on every pipeline stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best prior bench improvements came from removing reset fanout and dead\\npipeline metadata, while recent front-end and predictor changes lost Fmax.\\nThe current RTL still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and\\nMEM/WB even though most of those bits are only needed in EX. On a small FPGA\\nthis wastes flip-flops, mux inputs, and routing on every pipeline stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the monolithic ctrl_t payload into narrower downstream control records:\\nkeep the existing full ctrl_t only through ID/EX, replace EX/MEM control with\\njust the memory/writeback/trap bits consumed by MEM and hazard logic, and\\nreplace MEM/WB control with only reg_write, mem_to_reg, and is_illegal. This\\npreserves decode legality, branch/jump resolution, memory masks, RVFI fields,\\nand the nret=1 interface while pruning unused ALU, branch, jump, and immediate\\nselect metadata after EX.\\n\\nCPI should be unchanged because no behavior or timing protocol changes. The\\nexpected gain is a modest Fmax lift from narrower EX/MEM and MEM/WB registers,\\nlower control fanout, and simpler downstream muxing, following the same proven\\ndirection as the earlier dead-metadata pruning win without repeating the\\nmem_to_reg fanout mistake.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add narrow ex_mem_ctrl_t and mem_wb_ctrl_t records, then change ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t to use them instead of ...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Add posted store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\\nEX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\\nthat means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\\nwork even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\\npreserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\\nwhile the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\\nfront-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\\ndecoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\\ntraffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\\nEX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\\nthat means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\\nwork even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\\npreserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\\nwhile the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\\nfront-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\\ndecoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\\ntraffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry posted store buffer at the MEM stage. When a valid store\\nreaches EX/MEM while io_dmemReady is low and the buffer is empty, capture its\\naddress, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI sideband, let the store\\nretire exactly once through the normal channel-0 path, and allow subsequent\\nnon-memory instructions to keep flowing. The buffer continues driving the\\ndmem write r...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage learned target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core regressed because opcode/immediate decode,\\nBTB comparisons, return-shape checks, and predicted-next-PC muxing were placed on\\nthe IF next-PC path. CoreMark still pays a two-instruction penalty on recurring\\ntaken loop branches and direct jumps, so the remaining promising predictor angle\\nis to avoid the IF critical path while still reducing taken-control bubbles.\\n\\nA predictor consulted in ID can use the already-fetched PC/instruction timing\\npoint and redirect one cycle earlier than the current EX resolver. It only saves\\none of the two wrong-path slots, but it should cost less Fmax than full IF\\nspeculation and does not require early operand compare or immediate generation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core regressed because opcode/immediate decode,\\nBTB comparisons, return-shape checks, and predicted-next-PC muxing were placed on\\nthe IF next-PC path. CoreMark still pays a two-instruction penalty on recurring\\ntaken loop branches and direct jumps, so the remaining promising predictor angle\\nis to avoid the IF critical path while still reducing taken-control bubbles.\\n\\nA predictor consulted in ID can use the already-fetched PC/instruction timing\\npoint and redirect one cycle earlier than the current EX resolver. It only saves\\none of the two wrong-path slots, but it should cost less Fmax than full IF\\nspeculation and does not require early operand compare or immediate generation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped learned target predictor that is read in ID rather than\\nIF. EX remains the authoritative resolver and updates a small table with the PC,\\nresolved target, and a 2-bit taken counter for valid branches and jumps. When an\\ninstruction reaches ID, the predictor checks the IF/ID PC against the table tag;\\non a taken hit it sends an early redirect to IF u...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Reset only pipeline valid bits\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core is Fmax-sensitive and the strongest micro-opt wins came\\nfrom removing unnecessary reset fanout and dead pipeline metadata. The ID/EX,\\nEX/MEM, and MEM/WB pipeline registers still reset entire wide packed structs,\\nincluding RVFI data fields, operand values, immediates, memory data, and PC\\nmetadata that are ignored whenever valid is low. On the Tang Nano 20K this\\nreset muxing and fanout can cost routing and LUT delay without improving\\narchitectural behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core is Fmax-sensitive and the strongest micro-opt wins came\\nfrom removing unnecessary reset fanout and dead pipeline metadata. The ID/EX,\\nEX/MEM, and MEM/WB pipeline registers still reset entire wide packed structs,\\nincluding RVFI data fields, operand values, immediates, memory data, and PC\\nmetadata that are ignored whenever valid is low. On the Tang Nano 20K this\\nreset muxing and fanout can cost routing and LUT delay without improving\\narchitectural behavior.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Change the pipeline stage reset style so reset explicitly clears the validity\\nand side-effect control needed to prevent retirement, writes, memory requests,\\nredirects, and traps, while leaving data-only fields as don't-care until a\\nvalid instruction overwrites them. Preserve the existing bubble behavior for\\nflushes and MDU stalls by assigning zero payloads where the design relies on\\nthem, but avoid global reset of wide data members on every pipeline register.\\n\\nThis should reduce reset fanout and data-path muxing across the widest stage\\nboundaries without changing CPI, RVFI order, memory ordering, or the nret=1\\ntop-level interface. It follows the proven regfile-reset lesson while avoiding\\nprior failed control-bundle repacking and operand-source changes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\":...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Deepen posted store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The only recent structural improvement came from adding a one-entry posted store buffer, which lets an isolated store retire while its dmem write drains under random backpressure. That design still blocks when a second store arrives before the first buffered write is accepted, so short CoreMark store bursts can collapse back into full-pipeline stalls.\\n\\nFront-end structural changes have repeatedly regressed by adding fetch-path or replay complexity. A slightly deeper store queue stays in the proven back-end decoupling direction and avoids changing branch, fetch, or RVFI top-level semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only recent structural improvement came from adding a one-entry posted store buffer, which lets an isolated store retire while its dmem write drains under random backpressure. That design still blocks when a second store arrives before the first buffered write is accepted, so short CoreMark store bursts can collapse back into full-pipeline stalls.\\n\\nFront-end structural changes have repeatedly regressed by adding fetch-path or replay complexity. A slightly deeper store queue stays in the proven back-end decoupling direction and avoids changing branch, fetch, or RVFI top-level semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the single posted-store entry in mem_stage with a two-entry ordered store buffer. When a valid non-misaligned store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, enqueue it if either slot is free and still let that store retire exactly once through channel 0; the oldest buffered entry continues to drive the dmem write port until accepted. Younger loads and stores must stall behind any buffered store to preserve precise memory ordering, but younger non-memory instructions can continue as they do today.\\n\\nThis should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle in the random dmem-stall regime by absorbing back-to-back stores and store bursts, w...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Not-taken branch confidence predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core regressed because target prediction put\\ntag checks, immediate decode, next-PC muxing, and speculation metadata on the\\nfragile front-end path. The current core already fetches pc+4, which is the\\ncorrect path for not-taken conditional branches; the remaining predictor\\nopportunity is to make use of that cheap default without adding a target mux.\\n\\nCoreMark contains a mix of loop backedges and forward conditional exits. A\\nsmall direction-only confidence table can learn branches that are almost\\nalways not taken and let EX avoid asserting redirect/flush work for those\\ncorrectly predicted fall-through cases, while taken branches and jumps keep\\nusing the existing authoritative EX redirect path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core regressed because target prediction put\\ntag checks, immediate decode, next-PC muxing, and speculation metadata on the\\nfragile front-end path. The current core already fetches pc+4, which is the\\ncorrect path for not-taken conditional branches; the remaining predictor\\nopportunity is to make use of that cheap default without adding a target mux.\\n\\nCoreMark contains a mix of loop backedges and forward conditional exits. A\\nsmall direction-only confidence table can learn branches that are almost\\nalways not taken and let EX avoid asserting redirect/flush work for those\\ncorrectly predicted fall-through cases, while taken branches and jumps keep\\nusing the existing authoritative EX redirect path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped direction predictor that stores only conditional\\nbranch PCs and 2-bit not-taken/taken confidence counters. IF still always\\npresents pc+4 as the next fetch address; there is no predicted target path,\\nno branch immediate decode in IF, and no speculative target metadata. ID only\\ncarries a single predicted_not_...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Bypass ready load-use pairs\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\\na load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\\nthe data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\\narray dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\\nprovide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\\nfetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\\nloss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\\nreplay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\\na load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\\nthe data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\\narray dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\\nprovide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\\nfetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\\nloss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\\nreplay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated load-result forwarding path from mem_stage into ex_stage.\\nWhen a load has advanced into EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is high, mem_stage\\nalready computes the sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally; expose\\nthat value plus a valid/rd indication and teach forward_unit/ex_stage to use\\nit for the immediately following consumer instead of forwarding the load's\\naddress-valued alu_result. Change the load-use hazard so it stalls only when\\nthe producer load cannot...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage JAL target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Every prior predictor attempt for this core regressed because it put too much\\nwork on the fragile fetch next-PC path or carried broad prediction metadata\\nthrough the pipeline. CoreMark still contains direct calls and direct jumps\\nthat are always taken, and those currently wait until EX before redirecting,\\npaying two wrong-path slots each time. A predictor slot should therefore focus\\non the smallest control-flow case with a guaranteed direction and encoded\\ntarget.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Every prior predictor attempt for this core regressed because it put too much\\nwork on the fragile fetch next-PC path or carried broad prediction metadata\\nthrough the pipeline. CoreMark still contains direct calls and direct jumps\\nthat are always taken, and those currently wait until EX before redirecting,\\npaying two wrong-path slots each time. A predictor slot should therefore focus\\non the smallest control-flow case with a guaranteed direction and encoded\\ntarget.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static ID-stage predictor for JAL only. Decode already computes the\\nJ-immediate in ID, so when IF/ID holds a valid JAL the ID stage can request an\\nearly redirect to pc+imm one cycle before the existing EX resolver. Carry a\\nsingle predicted-direct-jump bit with the instruction so EX suppresses the\\nduplicate redirect only for the matching JAL; all conditional branches, JALR,\\nand misaligned target checks remain under the current authoritative EX path.\\n\\nThis avoids BTB/BHT state, tag comparators, return-stack logic, and IF-stage\\nimmediate decode while recovering one bubble for direct calls/jumps. The\\nexpected gain is modest but it is the predictor variant least likely to repeat\\nthe known Fmax regressions from broader front-end speculation.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\"...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative divider MDU\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current MDU moved RV32M work out of the common ALU path, but the real\\nhardware branch still uses SystemVerilog divide and remainder operators to\\ncompute DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally at start. Even with a 34-cycle\\nlatency counter, synthesis must build large divider/modulo cones that can\\nconsume LUTs and constrain placement on Tang Nano 20K. CoreMark's timed hot\\npath is dominated by RV32I plus occasional multiplies, so rare division\\nlatency is a better tradeoff than carrying a wide combinational divider.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current MDU moved RV32M work out of the common ALU path, but the real\\nhardware branch still uses SystemVerilog divide and remainder operators to\\ncompute DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally at start. Even with a 34-cycle\\nlatency counter, synthesis must build large divider/modulo cones that can\\nconsume LUTs and constrain placement on Tang Nano 20K. CoreMark's timed hot\\npath is dominated by RV32I plus occasional multiplies, so rare division\\nlatency is a better tradeoff than carrying a wide combinational divider.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU implementation in rtl/mdu.sv with a\\nsmall iterative restoring divider that reuses one subtract/compare step per\\ncycle and produces both quotient and remainder after roughly 32 cycles. Keep\\nthe existing interface, ALTOPS formulas, multiply results, divide-by-zero,\\nsigned overflow, and RV32M result semantics unchanged. This should reduce\\ndivider LUT/routing pressure and may improve median Fmax while leaving the\\ncommon RV32I pipeline, memory protocol, RVFI retirement, and nret=1 IO\\nuntouched. The CPI risk is limited because CoreMark rarely executes integer\\ndivision in the measured loop, and the old advertised divide latency was\\nalready multicycle.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\"...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage resolves both operand-forwarding mux selects with two\\n5-bit destination comparisons against EX/MEM and MEM/WB immediately before\\nthe ALU, branch comparator, MDU launch, and EX/MEM register boundary. After\\nthe successful MDU split, Tang Nano 20K fitness appears dominated by hot\\nRV32I timing and routing rather than rare long-latency M operations.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from removing common-path pressure, while attempts\\nto add front-end prediction, replay, or deeper queues regressed. Moving the\\nforwarding compare work one stage earlier is a structural retiming that keeps\\nfetch, branch resolution, memory ordering, and the nret=1 RVFI contract\\nunchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage resolves both operand-forwarding mux selects with two\\n5-bit destination comparisons against EX/MEM and MEM/WB immediately before\\nthe ALU, branch comparator, MDU launch, and EX/MEM register boundary. After\\nthe successful MDU split, Tang Nano 20K fitness appears dominated by hot\\nRV32I timing and routing rather than rare long-latency M operations.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from removing common-path pressure, while attempts\\nto add front-end prediction, replay, or deeper queues regressed. Moving the\\nforwarding compare work one stage earlier is a structural retiming that keeps\\nfetch, branch resolution, memory ordering, and the nret=1 RVFI contract\\nunchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute the EX operand forwarding selects while the consumer instruction is\\nstill in ID, comparing IF/ID rs1/rs2 against the instruction currently in EX\\nand the instruction currently in MEM. Latch those two 2-bit selects into the\\nID/EX payload, then make ex_stage use the precomputed selects directly for\\nits rs1/rs2 muxes.\\n\\nThis removes forward_unit's register-number comparator cone from the EX-stage\\nALU/branch critical path and...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Single backedge loop predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core lost fitness because they added IF\\ndecode, multi-entry tag/counter tables, return-stack checks, extra redirect\\nsources, or broad predicted-next-PC metadata to a timing-sensitive front end.\\nCoreMark still pays the full EX redirect penalty on hot counted-loop\\nbackedges, so the best predictor angle is a deliberately tiny loop-only\\ntarget predictor that learns one recurring taken backward branch without\\ntouching direct jumps, returns, or forward branches.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts for this core lost fitness because they added IF\\ndecode, multi-entry tag/counter tables, return-stack checks, extra redirect\\nsources, or broad predicted-next-PC metadata to a timing-sensitive front end.\\nCoreMark still pays the full EX redirect penalty on hot counted-loop\\nbackedges, so the best predictor angle is a deliberately tiny loop-only\\ntarget predictor that learns one recurring taken backward branch without\\ntouching direct jumps, returns, or forward branches.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry last-backedge predictor in if_stage. EX already computes\\nthe authoritative branch target and knows whether a conditional branch was\\ntaken; when that target is below the branch PC, record the branch PC and\\ntarget in two registers. IF predicts only on an exact PC match to that one\\nrecorded backedge, selecting the registered target instead of pc+4.\\n\\nTo avoid repeating the prior predictor regressions, do not add a BHT, BTB\\narray, return stack, IF immediate decode, or prediction metadata for jumps.\\nCarry only a one-bit predicted_backedge flag and the predicted target through\\nIF/ID and ID/EX so EX can suppress the duplicate redirect on a correct hit\\nor use the existing redirect/flush recovery on mismatch. This focuses the\\nhardware on the steady-state loop case most likely to help CoreMark while\\...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Decode explicit MDU op bit\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent bench results show the current core is more sensitive to Tang Nano 20K\\nFmax and routing than to speculative CPI tweaks. The EX stage still detects\\nRV32M operations by comparing the 5-bit ALU opcode against all eight MDU\\nencodings, then uses that result to drive the MDU start, EX busy/stall, result\\nmux, and RVFI operand capture paths. That decode sits in the hot execute\\ncontrol cone even though the decoder already knows exactly when funct7=1 marks\\nan M-extension instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent bench results show the current core is more sensitive to Tang Nano 20K\\nFmax and routing than to speculative CPI tweaks. The EX stage still detects\\nRV32M operations by comparing the 5-bit ALU opcode against all eight MDU\\nencodings, then uses that result to drive the MDU start, EX busy/stall, result\\nmux, and RVFI operand capture paths. That decode sits in the hot execute\\ncontrol cone even though the decoder already knows exactly when funct7=1 marks\\nan M-extension instruction.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single decoded control bit, for example ctrl_t.is_mdu, asserted only for\\nlegal RV32M OP instructions in rtl/decoder.sv and carried through ID/EX. Use\\nthis bit in rtl/ex_stage.sv instead of the current eight-way alu_op equality\\nchain when generating is_m_op, mdu_start, ex_busy, exec_result selection, and\\nMDU operand capture selection.\\n\\nThis intentionally adds one ID/EX control bit but removes repeated ALU-op\\ncomparisons from the common EX-stage control path. It does not alter MDU\\narithmetic, latencies, branch/fetch behavior, memory ordering, RVFI retirement,\\nor the nret=1 IO contract. The expected gain is a small median Fmax lift from\\nsimpler EX control with unchanged CoreMark CPI.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an is_mdu con...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Register final writeback data\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB boundary carries both alu_result and read_data plus a\\nmem_to_reg control bit, then wb_stage selects the final value on the same\\npath that drives regfile write data, MEM/WB forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata.\\nPrior successful structural work came from removing common-path pressure and\\npipeline metadata, while front-end replay/prediction changes and deeper\\nqueues have repeatedly regressed on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nA narrow back-end retiming can reduce late writeback muxing and MEM/WB\\nrouting without touching fetch, branch resolution, memory ordering, the\\nposted store buffer depth, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current MEM/WB boundary carries both alu_result and read_data plus a\\nmem_to_reg control bit, then wb_stage selects the final value on the same\\npath that drives regfile write data, MEM/WB forwarding, and RVFI rd_wdata.\\nPrior successful structural work came from removing common-path pressure and\\npipeline metadata, while front-end replay/prediction changes and deeper\\nqueues have repeatedly regressed on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nA narrow back-end retiming can reduce late writeback muxing and MEM/WB\\nrouting without touching fetch, branch resolution, memory ordering, the\\nposted store buffer depth, or the nret=1 RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a final wb_data field to the MEM/WB payload and compute it inside\\nmem_stage before the MEM/WB register captures: load instructions write the\\nalready sign/zero-extended load_data, while all other register-writing\\ninstructions write the EX/MEM alu_result. Then make wb_stage and the RVFI\\nrd_wdata path consume the registered wb_data directly, and remove the\\nlate mem_to_reg read_data/alu_result mux from the writeback/forwarding path.\\n\\nUnlike the earlier mem_to_reg pruning attempt, this does not make mem_read\\ndrive a wider fanout cone. It preserves the exist...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Next-line backedge predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves taken branches in EX and pays a two-instruction flush on every hot CoreMark loop backedge. Prior predictor attempts regressed because same-cycle IF decode, table reads, target muxes, and broad prediction metadata landed on the timing-sensitive fetch/control path. A predictor that prepares the likely next sequential PC one cycle ahead can target recurring backedges without putting a BTB lookup or immediate decode in the PC update cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves taken branches in EX and pays a two-instruction flush on every hot CoreMark loop backedge. Prior predictor attempts regressed because same-cycle IF decode, table reads, target muxes, and broad prediction metadata landed on the timing-sensitive fetch/control path. A predictor that prepares the likely next sequential PC one cycle ahead can target recurring backedges without putting a BTB lookup or immediate decode in the PC update cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry next-line backedge hint in if_stage. When EX resolves a taken conditional branch whose target is below its PC, record the branch PC and target. While fetching PC N, compare the recorded branch PC against N+4 and register a hint for the next sequential fetch; on the following cycle, if the PC is that hinted branch PC, select the already-registered target instead of pc+4.\\n\\nEX remains the authoritative resolver and updates the hint only from valid resolved branches. Carry only a predicted_backedge bit and predicted target through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can suppress the duplicate redirect on a correct hit or use the existing redirect/flush path on mismatch. This is narrower than the previous backedge predictor because the table compare is for pc+4 in the prior cycle and the IF PC mux consumes only a registered valid/target hint, reducing critical-path risk while preserving RV...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Share EX PC adders\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent micro-opt results show this core is Fmax-sensitive and benefits most\\nfrom removing redundant routing or datapath work without adding predictor or\\ncontrol metadata. The EX stage currently expresses the same PC additions in\\nseveral places: branch target, JAL target, JAL/JALR link value, and default\\npc_next each independently use `in.pc + in.imm` or `in.pc + 32'd4`. Even if\\nsynthesis shares some logic, making the sharing explicit should reduce adder\\nduplication, mux input depth, and routing pressure in the branch/jump EX cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent micro-opt results show this core is Fmax-sensitive and benefits most\\nfrom removing redundant routing or datapath work without adding predictor or\\ncontrol metadata. The EX stage currently expresses the same PC additions in\\nseveral places: branch target, JAL target, JAL/JALR link value, and default\\npc_next each independently use `in.pc + in.imm` or `in.pc + 32'd4`. Even if\\nsynthesis shares some logic, making the sharing explicit should reduce adder\\nduplication, mux input depth, and routing pressure in the branch/jump EX cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv to compute shared `pc_plus4` and `pc_imm_sum` wires\\nonce, then feed branch_target, non-JALR jump_target, JAL/JALR rd writeback,\\nand pc_next from those wires. Keep the existing JALR rs1+imm calculation,\\nmisalignment trap behavior, redirect timing, MDU behavior, RVFI pc_wdata\\nreporting, and nret=1 top-level interface unchanged.\\n\\nThis is a pure micro-optimization: CoreMark CPI should remain identical, but\\nmedian Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by trimming redundant 32-bit adders and\\nsimplifying the hot EX redirect/writeback muxing. The risk is low because it\\ndoes not alter pipeline state, hazard policy, memory ordering, or decoder\\nlegality.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"cha...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Split EX common add path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural wins came from removing common-path pressure in the back end,\\nwhile front-end replay, prediction, and deeper queues repeatedly regressed on\\nTang Nano 20K. The current EX stage still routes every ordinary register result\\nthrough the general ALU case mux, which includes compare and variable-shift\\nalternatives even for CoreMark's common add, immediate-add, load/store address,\\nAUIPC, and jump-link paths.\\n\\nA narrow EX-stage datapath split can reduce the hot forwarding-to-EX/MEM timing\\ncone without changing fetch, branch prediction, memory ordering, MDU behavior,\\nor the nret=1 RVFI retirement contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural wins came from removing common-path pressure in the back end,\\nwhile front-end replay, prediction, and deeper queues repeatedly regressed on\\nTang Nano 20K. The current EX stage still routes every ordinary register result\\nthrough the general ALU case mux, which includes compare and variable-shift\\nalternatives even for CoreMark's common add, immediate-add, load/store address,\\nAUIPC, and jump-link paths.\\n\\nA narrow EX-stage datapath split can reduce the hot forwarding-to-EX/MEM timing\\ncone without changing fetch, branch prediction, memory ordering, MDU behavior,\\nor the nret=1 RVFI retirement contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restructure ex_stage so common add-like operations use a dedicated fast result\\npath: compute add/sub/address/AUIPC/JAL link results separately from the general\\nshift/logic/compare ALU cone, then select the small fast result for ALU_ADD,\\nALU_SUB, ALU_LUI, AUIPC, load/store address generation, and JAL/JALR link writes.\\nKeep the existing alu.sv for less-common logic, compare, and shift operations,\\nand preserve the multicycle MDU launch/commit path exactly as today.\\n\\nThis should improve Fmax by keeping CoreMark's dominant integer/address path out\\nof the wide ALU o...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Metadata-free loop predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core still pays a two-instruction EX redirect penalty on taken\\nCoreMark loop backedges, but prior predictor attempts regressed mostly by\\nadding IF immediate decode, broad prediction metadata, extra redirect sources,\\nor learned tables that widened the fragile fetch and EX control paths. The\\nremaining predictor opportunity is therefore not a stronger predictor, but a\\nnarrower one: keep only the single hot-loop target case and remove the carried\\npredicted-next-PC metadata that hurt earlier variants.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core still pays a two-instruction EX redirect penalty on taken\\nCoreMark loop backedges, but prior predictor attempts regressed mostly by\\nadding IF immediate decode, broad prediction metadata, extra redirect sources,\\nor learned tables that widened the fragile fetch and EX control paths. The\\nremaining predictor opportunity is therefore not a stronger predictor, but a\\nnarrower one: keep only the single hot-loop target case and remove the carried\\npredicted-next-PC metadata that hurt earlier variants.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry taken-backedge predictor that records only the PC and target\\nof the most recent valid taken conditional branch whose target is below its PC.\\nIF predicts by exact PC match and selects the registered target; otherwise it\\nkeeps the existing pc+4 path. Unlike the prior single-entry and next-line\\nattempts, do not add predicted target fields to IF/ID or ID/EX. EX can infer\\nwhether this instruction was predicted from the same stable predictor entry\\nusing its retiring branch PC, suppress the duplicate redirect only when the\\nactual taken target matches the entry, and redirect to pc+4 on a predicted-hit\\nloop exit.\\n\\nThis preserves EX as the authoritative resolver and keeps RVFI pc_wdata/order\\nsemantics unchanged while reducing prediction metadata routing. The expe...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Drop stale load-select control\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already registers the final MEM/WB wb_data, so the old\\nload writeback select no longer fans into the writeback, forwarding, or RVFI\\nrd_wdata paths. However ctrl_t.mem_to_reg is still decoded, latched through\\nID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB, and routed alongside hotter control fields. Prior\\nmetadata-pruning wins show this FPGA build benefits when unnecessary control\\nrouting is removed, while broad structural changes have recently hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already registers the final MEM/WB wb_data, so the old\\nload writeback select no longer fans into the writeback, forwarding, or RVFI\\nrd_wdata paths. However ctrl_t.mem_to_reg is still decoded, latched through\\nID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB, and routed alongside hotter control fields. Prior\\nmetadata-pruning wins show this FPGA build benefits when unnecessary control\\nrouting is removed, while broad structural changes have recently hurt Fmax.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove ctrl_t.mem_to_reg and use the existing local load control in mem_stage\\nto select between sign/zero-extended load_data and the EX/MEM alu_result when\\nforming the registered wb_data. This revisits the earlier load-select pruning\\nonly after the successful final-wb-data retiming, so the selector no longer\\naffects the regfile, MEM/WB forwarding, or RVFI writeback fanout. CPI should\\nstay unchanged, and the narrower control bundle may improve Tang Nano 20K\\nplacement/routing enough to lift median Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the now-redundant ctrl_t.mem_to_reg field from the shared pipeline control bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the mem_to_reg output and assignments while preserving load legality, mem_read, reg_write, width, and sign controls.\"}...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Forward loads from store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best structural win is the one-entry posted store buffer, which\\nlets isolated stores retire while a stalled dmem write drains. Its remaining\\nconservative rule is that every younger memory operation stalls behind any\\nbuffered store, even when the younger load reads bytes wholly covered by that\\npending store. CoreMark stack and struct traffic can contain store-then-load\\npairs where random dmem backpressure currently turns a safe forwarding case\\ninto a full pipeline stall.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best structural win is the one-entry posted store buffer, which\\nlets isolated stores retire while a stalled dmem write drains. Its remaining\\nconservative rule is that every younger memory operation stalls behind any\\nbuffered store, even when the younger load reads bytes wholly covered by that\\npending store. CoreMark stack and struct traffic can contain store-then-load\\npairs where random dmem backpressure currently turns a safe forwarding case\\ninto a full pipeline stall.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add store-buffer load forwarding inside the existing MEM-stage decoupling\\nstructure. When the posted store buffer is full and the instruction in EX/MEM\\nis a valid, aligned load to the same word with a byte mask fully covered by\\nthe buffered store mask, synthesize the load word from the buffered replicated\\nstore data, let the load retire normally, and do not assert a dmem read for\\nthat forwarded access. Keep all nonmatching, partially covered, misaligned,\\nand store-following-memory cases stalled behind the buffer exactly as today.\\n\\nThis preserves precise in-order retirement, RVFI memory reporting, and the\\nnret=1 top-level contract while improving the useful decoupling of the proven\\none-entry store buffer. The change stays entirely in the back end, avoiding\\nthe front-end replay and prediction paths that repeatedly regresse...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Stable one-entry loop predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core still pays a two-instruction EX redirect penalty for every\\ntaken loop backedge, but the predictor history shows that broad IF decode,\\ntarget tables, return stacks, and wide predicted-next-PC metadata consistently\\nlose Fmax or break RVFI pc_fwd semantics. The one useful predictor target is\\nstill CoreMark's recurring counted-loop backedges, provided the design keeps\\nthe fetch path and metadata smaller than prior attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core still pays a two-instruction EX redirect penalty for every\\ntaken loop backedge, but the predictor history shows that broad IF decode,\\ntarget tables, return stacks, and wide predicted-next-PC metadata consistently\\nlose Fmax or break RVFI pc_fwd semantics. The one useful predictor target is\\nstill CoreMark's recurring counted-loop backedges, provided the design keeps\\nthe fetch path and metadata smaller than prior attempts.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry learned backedge predictor with stable per-instruction\\nprediction identity rather than mutable-state inference. EX records only a\\nvalid bit, branch PC, target, and a one-bit generation toggle when a valid\\nconditional branch is taken to a lower PC. IF predicts only on exact PC match\\nto that registered entry and selects the registered target instead of pc+4;\\nthere is no IF immediate decode, BHT, BTB array, RAS, or jump prediction.\\n\\nCarry only `pred_backedge` and the entry generation bit through IF/ID and\\nID/EX. EX suppresses the duplicate redirect only when the resolved branch PC,\\ntarget, and generation still match the prediction captured with that\\ninstruction; otherwise it uses the existing redirect/flush recovery. This\\nfixes the prior metadata-free correctness hazard without carrying a full\\npredicted target through the pipeline, aiming for a small CPI gain on hot\\nloops with less routing cost t...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Decode store byte masks\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent bench results show that this core is dominated by Tang Nano 20K Fmax\\nand routing pressure, while predictor, load-bypass, and control-repacking\\nchanges usually add more logic than CoreMark can recover. One remaining\\nsmall combinational cone is the MEM-stage byte-lane mask generation, which\\ncurrently uses variable shifts for byte and halfword accesses even though\\nthe mask set is only four fixed byte cases and two fixed halfword cases.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent bench results show that this core is dominated by Tang Nano 20K Fmax\\nand routing pressure, while predictor, load-bypass, and control-repacking\\nchanges usually add more logic than CoreMark can recover. One remaining\\nsmall combinational cone is the MEM-stage byte-lane mask generation, which\\ncurrently uses variable shifts for byte and halfword accesses even though\\nthe mask set is only four fixed byte cases and two fixed halfword cases.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the MEM-stage `4'b0001 << addr[1:0]` and `4'b0011 << addr[1:0]`\\nbyte-mask expressions with explicit fixed-mask decoding from `alu_result[1:0]`.\\nFor halfword accesses, use only `addr[1]` because misaligned halfword cases\\nare already trapped and never drive a real dmem write mask or RVFI memory\\nmask. This keeps the memory protocol, misalignment trap behavior, store\\nbuffer semantics, RVFI aligned-memory reporting, and nret=1 interface\\nunchanged while giving synthesis a smaller mux/decode cone in MEM.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable-shift byte_mask generation with explicit fixed byte/halfword mask decoding while preserving misalignment gating.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace variable-shift byte_mask...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Add narrow forwarding sideband\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already improved by registering final writeback data,\\nbut the EX forwarding decision still reaches back into the wide MEM/WB and\\nEX/MEM pipeline records for rd and reg_write metadata. Those packed records\\nalso feed RVFI, memory reporting, and hold-on-dmem-stall behavior, so their\\nhot fields can inherit unnecessary fanout and routing pressure on Tang Nano\\n20K.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from narrow back-end decoupling and retiming,\\nwhile front-end replay, prediction, deeper queues, and new same-cycle load\\npaths repeatedly regressed. A dedicated forwarding sideband keeps the proven\\npipeline behavior but gives synthesis a smaller set of signals for the EX\\noperand mux control cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already improved by registering final writeback data,\\nbut the EX forwarding decision still reaches back into the wide MEM/WB and\\nEX/MEM pipeline records for rd and reg_write metadata. Those packed records\\nalso feed RVFI, memory reporting, and hold-on-dmem-stall behavior, so their\\nhot fields can inherit unnecessary fanout and routing pressure on Tang Nano\\n20K.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from narrow back-end decoupling and retiming,\\nwhile front-end replay, prediction, deeper queues, and new same-cycle load\\npaths repeatedly regressed. A dedicated forwarding sideband keeps the proven\\npipeline behavior but gives synthesis a smaller set of signals for the EX\\noperand mux control cone.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add explicit narrow forwarding sideband signals for the two producer stages:\\nexmem_fwd_en/rd/data and memwb_fwd_en/rd/data. Drive them from the existing\\nregistered stage outputs, preserving the current semantics that MEM/WB may\\nremain forwardable during a dmem hold even when valid is cleared to avoid a\\ndouble retirement. Then make forward_unit consume only these sideband fields\\nin...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Stall-shadow branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core consistently lost fitness when they put\\ntarget lookup, immediate decode, extra PC muxing, or broad prediction metadata\\non the normal no-stall fetch path. CoreMark still pays taken-control penalties,\\nbut the benchmark also injects random instruction and data stalls that leave\\nthe front end holding a fetched instruction for one or more cycles. Those held\\ncycles are an opportunity to prepare a redirect without lengthening the common\\npc+4 fetch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core consistently lost fitness when they put\\ntarget lookup, immediate decode, extra PC muxing, or broad prediction metadata\\non the normal no-stall fetch path. CoreMark still pays taken-control penalties,\\nbut the benchmark also injects random instruction and data stalls that leave\\nthe front end holding a fetched instruction for one or more cycles. Those held\\ncycles are an opportunity to prepare a redirect without lengthening the common\\npc+4 fetch path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a stall-shadow predictor that only becomes active while IF/ID is already\\nblocked by imem backpressure, dmem backpressure, load-use, or MDU busy. During\\nthose held cycles, decode the currently presented instruction enough to\\nidentify direct JAL and backward conditional-branch candidates and compute\\ntheir static target off the normal PC-update critical path. When the stall\\nreleases, IF may use this precomputed target for a one-cycle early redirect;\\nEX remains authoritative and uses a single carried predicted-shadow bit plus\\npredicted target to suppress the duplicate redirect only on an exact match or\\nrepair through the existing redirect/flush path on mismatch.\\n\\nThis deliberately avoids BTB/BHT arrays, return stacks, same-cycle IF decode,\\nand prediction on uninterrupted fetch cycles. It should recover some control\\npen...\n  Line 38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"Pre-gate x0 producer enables\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent successful changes reduced routing pressure on hot back-end paths\\nwithout changing CPI, while predictor and broader control rewrites usually\\nlost Fmax. The current core still repeats zero-register destination checks in\\nseveral producer-consumer cones: writeback asserts w_en for rd=x0 and relies\\non reg_file to suppress it, forwarding sideband enables are true for rd=x0\\nand forward_unit rechecks rd!=0 for both operands, and RVFI computes its own\\nrd write-enable predicate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent successful changes reduced routing pressure on hot back-end paths\\nwithout changing CPI, while predictor and broader control rewrites usually\\nlost Fmax. The current core still repeats zero-register destination checks in\\nseveral producer-consumer cones: writeback asserts w_en for rd=x0 and relies\\non reg_file to suppress it, forwarding sideband enables are true for rd=x0\\nand forward_unit rechecks rd!=0 for both operands, and RVFI computes its own\\nrd write-enable predicate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Gate x0-producing instructions once when creating producer enables: make the\\nWB-stage write enable include rd!=0, make EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding\\nsideband enables include rd!=0, and then remove the duplicate rd!=0 checks\\nfrom forward_unit and the reg_file write port. Keep x0 read-as-zero behavior\\nand RVFI rd_addr/rd_wdata suppression unchanged. This should slightly shorten\\nthe forwarding compare/control cone and reduce small repeated comparators on\\na timing-sensitive design, with no change to pipeline timing, memory ordering,\\ntrap behavior, or the nret=1 top-level interface.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pre-gate exmem_fwd_en and memwb_fwd_en with rd!=0, and reuse the already gated writeback predicate where safe for RVFI writeback reporting.\"}...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"Split writeback commit sideband\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\\n\\nThe MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest structural improvement came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands so EX no longer depends directly on wide RVFI-heavy pipeline bundles. A similar fanout issue remains at the final writeback boundary: the full MEM/WB record still feeds regfile writeback, write-first register-file bypass, forwarding sideband generation, and RVFI reporting.\\n\\nThe MEM/WB record is intentionally wide because it carries PC, operand, memory, trap, and instruction metadata for RVFI. Those fields are cold for the hot regfile/writeback path, so keeping the commit datapath tied to the same packed struct can cost routing and mux delay on Tang Nano 20K without improving CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an explicit narrow writeback commit sideband alongside the existing MEM/WB RVFI record. The sideband should carry only valid, reg_write, rd, and the already-registered wb_data from mem_stage to wb_stage, the regfile write port, and the MEM/WB forwarding sideband. Keep the full mem_wb_t record for RVFI retirement and memory reporting only, with the same hold-on-dmem-stall semantics that prevent double retirement while preserving old forwarding data.\\n\\nThis is a structural isolation/re...\n  Line 40: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny learned JAL predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor history for this core shows that branch-direction tables, loop\\ntarget caches, return stacks, and static immediate decoding usually lose more\\nTang Nano 20K Fmax than they recover in CoreMark CPI. The remaining useful\\npredictor target should therefore avoid conditional branches, JALR returns,\\nIF immediate decoding, and wide predicted-next-PC metadata.\\n\\nDirect JAL call and jump sites are always taken and have stable targets in\\nCoreMark. Learning only the most recent direct JAL target gives a predictor\\nthat can recover recurring call/jump flushes with a single PC compare and a\\nregistered target, rather than a general branch predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor history for this core shows that branch-direction tables, loop\\ntarget caches, return stacks, and static immediate decoding usually lose more\\nTang Nano 20K Fmax than they recover in CoreMark CPI. The remaining useful\\npredictor target should therefore avoid conditional branches, JALR returns,\\nIF immediate decoding, and wide predicted-next-PC metadata.\\n\\nDirect JAL call and jump sites are always taken and have stable targets in\\nCoreMark. Learning only the most recent direct JAL target gives a predictor\\nthat can recover recurring call/jump flushes with a single PC compare and a\\nregistered target, rather than a general branch predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry learned direct-JAL target predictor. When EX resolves a valid\\nJAL, record the JAL PC, resolved target, and a one-bit generation tag. IF\\npredicts only when the current PC exactly matches that registered JAL PC,\\nselecting the registered target instead of pc+4; all conditional branches,\\nJALR, forward/backward branch heuristics, and return prediction remain on the\\nexisting non-speculative path.\\n\\nCarry only a predicted_jal bit and generation tag through IF/ID and ID/EX.\\nEX remains author...","metadata":{"matches":38,"truncated":false},"title":"category: structural|\"category\": \"structural\"|structural|split|stage|pipeline|retim|register|IF/ID|MEM/WB|EX/MEM","time":{"start":1778675374605,"end":1778675374626}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00d591025c8a9014016a046eae6824819abd2aae1dffa4f55d"}},"id":"prt_e21505a09001njaoR5sjpXnI5n","sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","messageID":"msg_e21501cb8001dDONdu0Q29GIgo"}}
