{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778675424087,"sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","part":{"id":"prt_e21511b54001wEB8ZRC4aIZS2d","messageID":"msg_e2151175200117DHQNEp3VQpT8","sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","snapshot":"eb94b7e7e0d14abe8a3404f1251afc4ae5e4183b","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778675462460,"sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","part":{"id":"prt_e2151adbd001fAhoKGuVXIJNY0","messageID":"msg_e2151175200117DHQNEp3VQpT8","sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the hypothesis file now. It uses the proven sideband-isolation pattern, but targets the EX/MEM memory-request and stall-control fanout instead of duplicating the failed writeback commit sideband.","time":{"start":1778675461565,"end":1778675462458},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00ac29c9480bb2ce016a046f05760c8198a5fa71c7d3a8967e","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778675487466,"sessionID":"ses_1deafe388ffeml2OEZjfriwPkq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_1wJQNMy2hY1bIK3WMLeyV2ms","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Isolate EX MEM request sideband\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The best recent structural result came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands\n+  so the EX operand-control cone no longer depended directly on wide RVFI-heavy\n+  pipeline records. The remaining back-end stall and memory-control path still\n+  reaches through the full EX/MEM bundle for mem_read, mem_write, address, store\n+  data, and width information while that same packed record also carries cold\n+  RVFI metadata. On Tang Nano 20K this can create unnecessary fanout and routing\n+  pressure even when CPI behavior is already good.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a narrow registered memory-request sideband at the EX/MEM boundary for the\n+  fields consumed by hazard_unit and mem_stage: valid, mem_read, mem_write,\n+  mem_width, mem_sext, effective address, store data, rd, and the small writeback\n+  controls needed to form wb_data. Keep the existing ex_mem_t record for RVFI PC,\n+  operand, instruction, and trap metadata, but stop using the full packed record\n+  as the hot memory/stall interface.\n+\n+  This mirrors the successful forwarding-sideband direction while avoiding the\n+  failed broad control-bundle split and duplicate commit sideband. It should\n+  preserve retirement order, store-buffer semantics, dmem backpressure behavior,\n+  and the nret=1 IO contract, while giving synthesis smaller local cones for the\n+  dmem port muxes and hazard stall decisions. CPI should be unchanged; any gain\n+  should come from Fmax and routing improvement.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a compact ex_mem_req_t sideband type carrying only the registered memory-request and writeback-control fields needed after EX.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Populate the new memory-request sideband in parallel with the existing EX/MEM RVFI record, preserving MDU, redirect, trap, and pc_next behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the narrow EX/MEM memory sideband to hazard_unit and mem_stage so hot stall/control logic no longer fans out through the full ex_mem_t bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrow memory-request sideband for dmem address, masks, load extraction, store buffering, and wb_data formation while retaining ex_mem_t only for RVFI metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Use the sideband's mem_read and mem_write indicators for dmem stall decisions without changing load-use, redirect, MDU, or store-buffer ordering policy.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,39 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Isolate EX MEM request sideband\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The best recent structural result came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands\n+  so the EX operand-control cone no longer depended directly on wide RVFI-heavy\n+  pipeline records. The remaining back-end stall and memory-control path still\n+  reaches through the full EX/MEM bundle for mem_read, mem_write, address, store\n+  data, and width information while that same packed record also carries cold\n+  RVFI metadata. On Tang Nano 20K this can create unnecessary fanout and routing\n+  pressure even when CPI behavior is already good.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a narrow registered memory-request sideband at the EX/MEM boundary for the\n+  fields consumed by hazard_unit and mem_stage: valid, mem_read, mem_write,\n+  mem_width, mem_sext, effective address, store data, rd, and the small writeback\n+  controls needed to form wb_data. Keep the existing ex_mem_t record for RVFI PC,\n+  operand, instruction, and trap metadata, but stop using the full packed record\n+  as the hot memory/stall interface.\n+\n+  This mirrors the successful forwarding-sideband direction while avoiding the\n+  failed broad control-bundle split and duplicate commit sideband. It should\n+  preserve retirement order, store-buffer semantics, dmem backpressure behavior,\n+  and the nret=1 IO contract, while giving synthesis smaller local cones for the\n+  dmem port muxes and hazard stall decisions. CPI should be unchanged; any gain\n+  should come from Fmax and routing improvement.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a compact ex_mem_req_t sideband type carrying only the registered memory-request and writeback-control fields needed after EX.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Populate the new memory-request sideband in parallel with the existing EX/MEM RVFI record, preserving MDU, redirect, trap, and pc_next behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the narrow EX/MEM memory sideband to hazard_unit and mem_stage so hot stall/control logic no longer fans out through the full ex_mem_t bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrow memory-request sideband for dmem address, masks, load extraction, store buffering, and wb_data formation while retaining ex_mem_t only for RVFI metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Use the sideband's mem_read and mem_write indicators for dmem stall decisions without changing load-use, redirect, MDU, or store-buffer ordering policy.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r14s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,39 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r14s1\n+title: \"Isolate EX MEM request sideband\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The best recent structural result came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands\n+  so the EX operand-control cone no longer depended directly on wide RVFI-heavy\n+  pipeline records. The remaining back-end stall and memory-control path still\n+  reaches through the full EX/MEM bundle for mem_read, mem_write, address, store\n+  data, and width information while that same packed record also carries cold\n+  RVFI metadata. On Tang Nano 20K this can create unnecessary fanout and routing\n+  pressure even when CPI behavior is already good.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a narrow registered memory-request sideband at the EX/MEM boundary for the\n+  fields consumed by hazard_unit and mem_stage: valid, mem_read, mem_write,\n+  mem_width, mem_sext, effective address, store data, rd, and the small writeback\n+  controls needed to form wb_data. Keep the existing ex_mem_t record for RVFI PC,\n+  operand, instruction, and trap metadata, but stop using the full packed record\n+  as the hot memory/stall interface.\n+\n+  This mirrors the successful forwarding-sideband direction while avoiding the\n+  failed broad control-bundle split and duplicate commit sideband. It should\n+  preserve retirement order, store-buffer semantics, dmem backpressure behavior,\n+  and the nret=1 IO contract, while giving synthesis smaller local cones for the\n+  dmem port muxes and hazard stall decisions. CPI should be unchanged; any gain\n+  should come from Fmax and routing improvement.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add a compact ex_mem_req_t sideband type carrying only the registered memory-request and writeback-control fields needed after EX.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Populate the new memory-request sideband in parallel with the existing EX/MEM RVFI record, preserving MDU, redirect, trap, and pc_next behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the narrow EX/MEM memory sideband to hazard_unit and mem_stage so hot stall/control logic no longer fans out through the full ex_mem_t bundle.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the narrow memory-request sideband for dmem address, masks, load extraction, store buffering, and wb_data formation while retaining ex_mem_t only for RVFI metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Use the sideband's mem_read and mem_write indicators for dmem stall decisions without changing load-use, redirect, MDU, or store-buffer ordering policy.\"\n","additions":39,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp