ssure behavior,\n23:   and the nret=1 IO contract, while giving synthesis smaller local cones for the\n24:   dmem port muxes and hazard stall decisions. CPI should be unchanged; any gain\n25:   should come from Fmax and routing improvement.\n26: expected_impact:\n27:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n28:   confidence: medium\n29: changes:\n30:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n31:     description: \"Add a compact ex_mem_req_t sideband type carrying only the registered memory-request and writeback-control fields needed after EX.\"\n32:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n33:     description: \"Populate the new memory-request sideband in parallel with the existing EX/MEM RVFI record, preserving MDU, redirect, trap, and pc_next behavior.\"\n34:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n35:     description: \"Wire the narrow EX/MEM memory sideband to hazard_unit and mem_stage so hot stall/control logic no longer fans out through the full ex_mem_t bundle.\"\n36:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n37:     description: \"Consume the narrow memory-request sideband for dmem address, masks, load extraction, store buffering, and wb_data formation while retaining ex_mem_t only for RVFI metadata.\"\n38:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n39:     description: \"Use the sideband's mem_read and mem_write indicators for dmem stall decisions without changing load-use, redirect, MDU, or store-buffer ordering policy.\"\n\n(End of file - total 39 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r14s1\ntitle: \"Isolate EX MEM request sideband\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The best recent structural result came from adding narrow forwarding sidebands\n  so the EX operand-control cone no longer depended directly on wide RVFI-heavy\n  pipeline records. The remaining back-end stall and memory-control path still\n  reaches through the full EX/MEM bundle for mem_read, mem_write, address, store\n  data, and width information while that same packed record also carries cold\n  RVFI metadata. On Tang Nano 20K this can create u