{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778659611339,"sessionID":"ses_1dfa17494ffe6uTyrmdxXbFkDg","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_zKK8E6N62CQhWsKjQLtcylac","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\n+  remainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\n+  CoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\n+  synthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\n+  EX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\n+\n+  CoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\n+  operations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\n+  a favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\n+  multicycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\n+  for add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\n+  ALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\n+  half of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\n+  into the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\n+  stay unchanged.\n+\n+  This structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\n+  divider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should be\n+  limited because CoreMark's counted loops are not dominated by M-extension\n+  arithmetic, while every non-M instruction benefits from the shorter path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Remove RV32M multiply/divide/remainder hardware from the common combinational ALU path, keeping only the ALTOPS formal substitutions or routing M ops through an external result path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mdu.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small multicycle RV32M execution unit with start/busy/done/result handshake and exact RV32IM division overflow and divide-by-zero semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect M-extension ALU ops, launch and wait for the MDU, hold the ID/EX instruction while busy, and commit the MDU result through the existing EX/MEM retirement path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX-stage multicycle stall input that freezes fetch/decode and prevents younger instructions from advancing while the MDU owns the execute stage.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the MDU busy/done stall path between EX and the hazard unit without changing the nret=1 top-level IO or RVFI channel-0 contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\n+  remainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\n+  CoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\n+  synthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\n+  EX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\n+\n+  CoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\n+  operations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\n+  a favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\n+  multicycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\n+  for add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\n+  ALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\n+  half of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\n+  into the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\n+  stay unchanged.\n+\n+  This structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\n+  divider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should be\n+  limited because CoreMark's counted loops are not dominated by M-extension\n+  arithmetic, while every non-M instruction benefits from the shorter path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Remove RV32M multiply/divide/remainder hardware from the common combinational ALU path, keeping only the ALTOPS formal substitutions or routing M ops through an external result path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mdu.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small multicycle RV32M execution unit with start/busy/done/result handshake and exact RV32IM division overflow and divide-by-zero semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect M-extension ALU ops, launch and wait for the MDU, hold the ID/EX instruction while busy, and commit the MDU result through the existing EX/MEM retirement path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX-stage multicycle stall input that freezes fetch/decode and prevents younger instructions from advancing while the MDU owns the execute stage.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the MDU busy/done stall path between EX and the hazard unit without changing the nret=1 top-level IO or RVFI channel-0 contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\n+  remainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\n+  CoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\n+  synthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\n+  EX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\n+\n+  CoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\n+  operations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\n+  a favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\n+  multicycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\n+  for add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\n+  ALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\n+  half of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\n+  into the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\n+  stay unchanged.\n+\n+  This structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\n+  divider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should be\n+  limited because CoreMark's counted loops are not dominated by M-extension\n+  arithmetic, while every non-M instruction benefits from the shorter path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Remove RV32M multiply/divide/remainder hardware from the common combinational ALU path, keeping only the ALTOPS formal substitutions or routing M ops through an external result path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mdu.sv\n+    description: \"Add a small multicycle RV32M execution unit with start/busy/done/result handshake and exact RV32IM division overflow and divide-by-zero semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect M-extension ALU ops, launch and wait for the MDU, hold the ID/EX instruction while busy, and commit the MDU result through the existing EX/MEM retirement path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add an EX-stage multicycle stall input that freezes fetch/decode and prevents younger instructions from advancing while the MDU owns the execute stage.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the MDU busy/done stall path between EX and the hazard unit without changing the nret=1 top-level IO or RVFI channel-0 contract.\"\n","additions":40,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":f