{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778659630578,"sessionID":"ses_1dfa17494ffe6uTyrmdxXbFkDg","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Oj2YorC1FNWrZ3T0f3piUToX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\n2: title: \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\n6:   remainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\n7:   CoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\n8:   synthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\n9:   EX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\n10: \n11:   CoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\n12:   operations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\n13:   a favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\n14: hypothesis: |\n15:   Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\n16:   multicycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\n17:   for add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\n18:   ALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\n19:   half of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\n20:   into the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\n21:   stay unchanged.\n22: \n23:   This structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\n24:   divider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should be\n25:   limited because CoreMark's counted loops are not dominated by M-extension\n26:   arithmetic, while every non-M instruction benefits from the shorter path.\n27: expected_impact:\n28:   fitness_delta_pct: 6\n29:   confidence: medium\n30: changes:\n31:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n32:     description: \"Remove RV32M multiply/divide/remainder hardware from the common combinational ALU path, keeping only the ALTOPS formal substitutions or routing M ops through an external result path.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/mdu.sv\n34:     description: \"Add a small multicycle RV32M execution unit with start/busy/done/result handshake and exact RV32IM division overflow and divide-by-zero semantics.\"\n35:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n36:     description: \"Detect M-extension ALU ops, launch and wait for the MDU, hold the ID/EX instruction while busy, and commit the MDU result through the existing EX/MEM retirement path.\"\n37:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n38:     description: \"Add an EX-stage multicycle stall input that freezes fetch/decode and prevents younger instructions from advancing while the MDU owns the execute stage.\"\n39:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n40:     description: \"Wire the MDU busy/done stall path between EX and the hazard unit without changing the nret=1 top-level IO or RVFI channel-0 contract.\"\n\n(End of file - total 40 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\ntitle: \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\n  remainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\n  CoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\n  synthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\n  EX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\n\n  CoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\n  operations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\n  a favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\n  multicycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\n  for add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\n  ALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\n  half of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\n  into the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r2s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778659630568,"end":1778659630577}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0010ba62abe2bef1016a04312b3a908199bb383c0de60de66d"}},"id":"prt_e20601142001ZCtEbYM5VhRwzn","sessionID":"ses_1dfa17494ffe6uTyrmdxXbFkDg","messageID":"msg_e205fd33c002z9hxdna98jlyuF"}}
