{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778661486226,"sessionID":"ses_1df852e9effeLUwZ055H2LGRh6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_vKOlRBKgfs5begvucyNAZAVV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n+title: \"Add one-entry fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\n+  the PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\n+  random instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\n+  this tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\n+  cycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\n+  fetched word.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\n+  front-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\n+  the fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\n+  it should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\n+  the existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry IF/ID fetch skid buffer in the front end. When imemReady is\n+  high but decode is stalled by load-use, dmem backpressure, or an MDU busy\n+  period, capture the current fetched instruction and PC instead of emitting a\n+  bubble or requiring the instruction bus to be ready again later. When decode\n+  becomes available, drain the buffered instruction before advancing to newer\n+  fetch data.\n+\n+  Redirects must invalidate the buffer and retain the existing priority where\n+  the EX redirect updates the PC even during stalls. The buffer should not try\n+  to predict branches or move resolution earlier; it only decouples fetch from\n+  decode acceptance. This should raise CoreMark iterations/cycle in the random\n+  iStall workload with modest LUT/FF cost and lower correctness risk than\n+  branch-control restructuring.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready fetch data while decode is stalled and flushes on reset or EX redirect.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Pass decode-accept or front-end stall intent into IF so the buffer can distinguish PC hold from IF/ID payload retention without changing the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Refine stall/flush outputs as needed so imem stalls still bubble when no buffered instruction exists, while backend stalls allow buffered fetch data to be retained and replayed.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n+title: \"Add one-entry fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\n+  the PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\n+  random instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\n+  this tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\n+  cycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\n+  fetched word.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\n+  front-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\n+  the fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\n+  it should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\n+  the existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry IF/ID fetch skid buffer in the front end. When imemReady is\n+  high but decode is stalled by load-use, dmem backpressure, or an MDU busy\n+  period, capture the current fetched instruction and PC instead of emitting a\n+  bubble or requiring the instruction bus to be ready again later. When decode\n+  becomes available, drain the buffered instruction before advancing to newer\n+  fetch data.\n+\n+  Redirects must invalidate the buffer and retain the existing priority where\n+  the EX redirect updates the PC even during stalls. The buffer should not try\n+  to predict branches or move resolution earlier; it only decouples fetch from\n+  decode acceptance. This should raise CoreMark iterations/cycle in the random\n+  iStall workload with modest LUT/FF cost and lower correctness risk than\n+  branch-control restructuring.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry valid/pc/instruction skid buffer that captures ready fetch data while decode is stalled and flushes on reset or EX redirect.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Pass decode-accept or front-end stall intent into IF so the buffer can distinguish PC hold from IF/ID payload retention without changing the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Refine stall/flush outputs as needed so imem stalls still bubble when no buffered instruction exists, while backend stalls allow buffered fetch data to be retained and replayed.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n+title: \"Add one-entry fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\n+  the PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\n+  random instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\n+  this tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\n+  cycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\n+  fetched word.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\n+  front-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\n+  the fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\n+  it should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\n+  the existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry IF/ID fetch skid buffer in the front end. When imemReady is\n+  high but decode is stalled by load-use, dmem backpressure, or an MDU busy\n+  period, capture the current fetched instruction and PC instead of em