{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778663180382,"sessionID":"ses_1df6a0176ffevdE76ufkR1w8iY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_0JDIpKORs2QBIKAek54epWcn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: structural|structural|pipeline|stage|register|metadata|critical|Fmax|skid|buffer|bypass","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 9 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Remove regfile reset fanout\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a\\nsynchronous for-loop. On FPGA this discourages LUTRAM-style inference for the\\n32x32 storage and adds reset muxing/fanout across a hot, frequently accessed\\nstructure. RV32I does not require integer registers other than x0 to have a\\ndefined reset value, and x0 is already hardwired through read/write gating.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current register file resets all 32 architectural registers with a\\nsynchronous for-loop. On FPGA this discourages LUTRAM-style inference for the\\n32x32 storage and adds reset muxing/fanout across a hot, frequently accessed\\nstructure. RV32I does not require integer registers other than x0 to have a\\ndefined reset value, and x0 is already hardwired through read/write gating.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Change rtl/reg_file.sv so reset no longer clears the backing register array.\\nPreserve the existing write-first bypass, x0 read-as-zero behavior, and write\\nsuppression to x0. This should reduce flip-flop/reset routing pressure and may\\nlet synthesis map the register file to distributed RAM or a smaller muxed\\nstructure, improving Fmax with negligible CoreMark CPI risk because compiled C\\ncode initializes live registers before use.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 hardwiring and write-first read bypass semantics.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the synchronous reset loop over regs[0:31] while preserving x0 hardwiring and write-first read bypass semantics.\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 316.22, \"delta_pct\": 11.81, \"vs_baseline\": 11.81, \"fmax_mhz\": 142.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"c...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve branches in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every branch and jump in EX, so each\\ntaken redirect flushes two younger instructions. CoreMark spends many cycles\\nin tight counted loops and function-call-heavy list/state code, making taken\\ncontrol transfers a direct CPI cost. Reducing the redirect penalty by one\\nstage should improve iterations per cycle without changing the nret=1 RVFI\\ncontract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every branch and jump in EX, so each\\ntaken redirect flushes two younger instructions. CoreMark spends many cycles\\nin tight counted loops and function-call-heavy list/state code, making taken\\ncontrol transfers a direct CPI cost. Reducing the redirect penalty by one\\nstage should improve iterations per cycle without changing the nret=1 RVFI\\ncontract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an ID-stage early redirect path for conditional branches, JAL, and JALR\\nwhen their operands are already available from the regfile or safe same-cycle\\nbypasses. The ID stage can compute immediates, branch comparisons, and jump\\ntargets one cycle earlier than EX; when it redirects, IF emits a bubble and\\nID/EX captures a bubble so the control-transfer instruction still retires\\nthrough the normal pipeline with correct RVFI pc_wdata. Cases needing an\\nunavailable producer, especially load-use and EX/MEM load results, fall back\\nto the existing EX resolution path for correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire an early ID redirect signal into IF and hazard control while preserving the existing EX redirect fallback and single-channel RVFI retirement.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute branch and jump targets in ID, compare available operands with WB bypassing, emit an early redirect, and carry the resolved pc_next metadat...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Add tiny BTB and BHT branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always fetches pc+4 and resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken control-flow instruction pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark contains tight loops and repeated call/return style control flow where even a very small FPGA-friendly predictor should learn the hot backedges and reduce bubbles. A predictor is especially attractive under the random instruction-stall workload because it improves useful fetch placement without adding memory-system complexity.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always fetches pc+4 and resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken control-flow instruction pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark contains tight loops and repeated call/return style control flow where even a very small FPGA-friendly predictor should learn the hot backedges and reduce bubbles. A predictor is especially attractive under the random instruction-stall workload because it improves useful fetch placement without adding memory-system complexity.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with 2-bit saturating direction counters in the IF stage. The IF stage predicts taken when the PC tag hits and the BHT counter is weak/strong taken, uses the cached target as next_pc, and carries predicted_pc/predicted_taken metadata down the pipeline. EX compares the actual resolved next PC against the prediction, redirects only on mispredict, and updates the BTB/BHT for branches and jumps. This should preserve correctness through the existing redirect/flush machinery while converting most steady-state CoreMark loop backedges from taken-branch flushes into correctly predicted fetches.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipel...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Qualify load-use source checks\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against both\\nraw source bitfields of the following instruction for every opcode. For many\\nRV32I instructions, one or both of those bitfields are immediate bits or are\\notherwise unused, so a coincidental match with the prior load's rd injects a\\nneedless one-cycle bubble. CoreMark has frequent loads followed by immediate\\narithmetic, address updates, jumps, and upper-immediate instructions where\\navoiding false dependencies should improve iterations per cycle without\\ntouching the proven datapath or memory protocol.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard detector compares a load destination against both\\nraw source bitfields of the following instruction for every opcode. For many\\nRV32I instructions, one or both of those bitfields are immediate bits or are\\notherwise unused, so a coincidental match with the prior load's rd injects a\\nneedless one-cycle bubble. CoreMark has frequent loads followed by immediate\\narithmetic, address updates, jumps, and upper-immediate instructions where\\navoiding false dependencies should improve iterations per cycle without\\ntouching the proven datapath or memory protocol.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Teach the hazard unit which IF/ID operands are actually consumed before\\napplying the load-use comparison. Keep the true load-use stall for branches,\\nstores, R-type operations, JALR, OP-IMM rs1 uses, and real load base-register\\ndependencies, but ignore rs2 for I-type/load/JALR immediates and ignore both\\noperands for LUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and EBREAK. This is a small combinational\\ndecode in the existing hazard path that should remove spurious bubbles while\\npreserving all forwarding, RVFI order, trap, and bus-stall behavior.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"de...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\\nremainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\\nCoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\\nsynthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\\nEX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\\noperations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\\na favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\\nremainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\\nCoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\\nsynthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\\nEX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\\noperations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\\na favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\\nmulticycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\\nfor add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\\nALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\\nhalf of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\\ninto the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\\nstay unchanged.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\\ndivider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should b...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches pc+4 and pays a two-instruction\\nredirect penalty for every taken branch and jump resolved in EX. CoreMark has\\nmany small counted loops where backward conditional branches are taken most\\niterations, plus direct JAL call/loop control transfers with targets fully\\nencoded in the fetched instruction. A tiny static predictor can recover much\\nof that CPI loss with less state and less correctness risk than the previous\\nBTB/BHT attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core always fetches pc+4 and pays a two-instruction\\nredirect penalty for every taken branch and jump resolved in EX. CoreMark has\\nmany small counted loops where backward conditional branches are taken most\\niterations, plus direct JAL call/loop control transfers with targets fully\\nencoded in the fetched instruction. A tiny static predictor can recover much\\nof that CPI loss with less state and less correctness risk than the previous\\nBTB/BHT attempt.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add decode-light prediction in IF for direct control flow only: predict JAL\\ntaken to its J-immediate target, predict conditional branches with negative\\nB-immediates taken, and leave forward branches plus JALR as pc+4. Carry the\\npredicted next PC with the instruction through IF/ID and ID/EX. EX still\\ncomputes the authoritative next PC and RVFI pc_wdata, but redirects and\\nflushes only when the predicted next PC differs from the actual next PC.\\nThis keeps the existing retirement semantics intact while eliminating the\\nsteady-state flush on hot backward CoreMark loop branches and direct jumps.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can compare speculation against the resolved next PC without changing RV...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead pipeline metadata\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current post-MDU core is Fmax-sensitive enough that small reductions in\\npipeline register width and hot-stage routing can still move Tang Nano 20K\\nfitness. Several metadata fields are carried after decode/execute but are not\\nconsumed by any later stage or by RVFI: LUI is already represented by\\nalu_op=ALU_LUI plus alu_src, and EX-stage branch_taken/branch_target are only\\nused locally before being redundantly flopped into EX/MEM.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current post-MDU core is Fmax-sensitive enough that small reductions in\\npipeline register width and hot-stage routing can still move Tang Nano 20K\\nfitness. Several metadata fields are carried after decode/execute but are not\\nconsumed by any later stage or by RVFI: LUI is already represented by\\nalu_op=ALU_LUI plus alu_src, and EX-stage branch_taken/branch_target are only\\nused locally before being redundantly flopped into EX/MEM.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove dead metadata from the pipeline bundles and the wiring that feeds it:\\ndrop ctrl_t.is_lui and the decoder/id-stage plumbing for it, and drop\\nex_mem_t.branch_taken plus ex_mem_t.branch_target and their EX-stage register\\nassignments. This should reduce flip-flops, mux inputs, and routing pressure\\nacross ID/EX and EX/MEM without changing instruction semantics, branch\\nredirect timing, memory behavior, or the nret=1 RVFI retirement interface.\\nBecause the change is pure metadata pruning, CPI should be unchanged while\\nmedian Fmax may improve modestly.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove unused ctrl_t.is_lui and dead ex_mem_t branch_taken/branch_target fields from the pipeline bundle definitions.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the unused is_lui output and its assignments while preserving LUI legality, ALU_LUI select...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Add one-entry fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\\nthe PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\\nrandom instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\\nthis tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\\ncycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\\nfetched word.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\\nfront-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\\nthe fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\\nit should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\\nthe existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\\nthe PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\\nrandom instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\\nthis tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\\ncycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\\nfetched word.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\\nfront-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\\nthe fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\\nit should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\\nthe existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry IF/ID fetch skid buffer in the front end. When imemReady is\\nhigh but decode is stalled by load-use, dmem backpressure, or an MDU busy\\nperiod, capture the current fetched instruction and PC instead of emitting a\\nbubble or requiring the instruction bus to be ...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny return address predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The previous predictor attempts show that putting branch-immediate decode or\\nBTB/BHT lookup directly on the IF next-PC path can either break RVFI redirect\\nsemantics or lose enough Fmax to erase loop CPI gains. CoreMark still has many\\ncall and return transfers, and returns are expensive in the current core\\nbecause every JALR resolves in EX and flushes two younger instructions.\\n\\nA very small return-address predictor targets only the indirect-control case\\nthat static backward prediction cannot cover, while avoiding a broad branch\\ndirection predictor in the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous predictor attempts show that putting branch-immediate decode or\\nBTB/BHT lookup directly on the IF next-PC path can either break RVFI redirect\\nsemantics or lose enough Fmax to erase loop CPI gains. CoreMark still has many\\ncall and return transfers, and returns are expensive in the current core\\nbecause every JALR resolves in EX and flushes two younger instructions.\\n\\nA very small return-address predictor targets only the indirect-control case\\nthat static backward prediction cannot cover, while avoiding a broad branch\\ndirection predictor in the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a 2- or 4-entry return-address stack that pushes pc+4 for ordinary direct\\ncalls and predicts JALR returns when the fetched instruction matches the\\nstandard return shape, such as JALR x0, x1, 0 or JALR x0, x5, 0. The IF stage\\nshould keep the normal pc+4 path for all other instructions, so the added\\nlogic is a narrow opcode/funct/rd/rs1/imm equality check plus a small mux to a\\nregistered stack top.\\n\\nCarry predicted-next-PC metadata with the instruction and keep EX as the\\nauthoritative resolver. On mismatch, use the existing redirect/flush path; on\\nmatch, suppress only the unnecessary redirect flush while preserving RVFI\\npc_wdata from E...","metadata":{"matches":9,"truncated":false},"title":"category: structural|structural|pipeline|stage|register|metadata|critical|Fmax|skid|buffer|bypass","time":{"start":1778663180366,"end":1778663180381}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08b0d096da2a1699016a043f0c32e4819a82d831ed014d6dad"}},"id":"prt_e2096484b001ZShj9yNn0tIFKk","sessionID":"ses_1df6a0176ffevdE76ufkR1w8iY","messageID":"msg_e2095fefa001YMdZTvd9veywZR"}}
