{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778664239276,"sessionID":"ses_1df5b277effeiZDCj1aKs4bhnS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_kStKZZBR09DI6mg79XnQSlIU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Add posted store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\n+  EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\n+  that means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\n+  work even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\n+  preserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\n+  while the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\n+  front-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\n+  decoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\n+  traffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry posted store buffer at the MEM stage. When a valid store\n+  reaches EX/MEM while io_dmemReady is low and the buffer is empty, capture its\n+  address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI sideband, let the store\n+  retire exactly once through the normal channel-0 path, and allow subsequent\n+  non-memory instructions to keep flowing. The buffer continues driving the\n+  dmem write request until io_dmemReady accepts it.\n+\n+  To preserve precise in-order memory behavior, stall any later load or store\n+  while the buffer is occupied, and keep the existing full-pipeline dmem stall\n+  behavior when a load misses readiness or when a second store arrives before\n+  the buffer drains. This should recover cycles otherwise lost to isolated\n+  store backpressure under the apples-to-apples random stall model, with a\n+  smaller Fmax risk than fetch-side structural changes because the added state\n+  sits behind EX/MEM and does not affect branch redirect or PC selection.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Optionally add a compact store-buffer payload type or reuse existing EX/MEM fields needed to hold address, data, mask, and RVFI retirement metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement the one-entry posted store buffer, retire an accepted-to-buffer store once, continue driving buffered writes until dmemReady, and block younger memory operations while buffered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Distinguish load stalls and full-buffer/younger-memory stalls from isolated store backpressure so non-memory instructions can proceed behind a buffered store.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status between MEM and hazard control while keeping the nret=1 RVFI port set and channel-0 retirement order unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,42 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Add posted store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\n+  EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\n+  that means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\n+  work even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\n+  preserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\n+  while the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\n+  front-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\n+  decoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\n+  traffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry posted store buffer at the MEM stage. When a valid store\n+  reaches EX/MEM while io_dmemReady is low and the buffer is empty, capture its\n+  address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI sideband, let the store\n+  retire exactly once through the normal channel-0 path, and allow subsequent\n+  non-memory instructions to keep flowing. The buffer continues driving the\n+  dmem write request until io_dmemReady accepts it.\n+\n+  To preserve precise in-order memory behavior, stall any later load or store\n+  while the buffer is occupied, and keep the existing full-pipeline dmem stall\n+  behavior when a load misses readiness or when a second store arrives before\n+  the buffer drains. This should recover cycles otherwise lost to isolated\n+  store backpressure under the apples-to-apples random stall model, with a\n+  smaller Fmax risk than fetch-side structural changes because the added state\n+  sits behind EX/MEM and does not affect branch redirect or PC selection.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Optionally add a compact store-buffer payload type or reuse existing EX/MEM fields needed to hold address, data, mask, and RVFI retirement metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement the one-entry posted store buffer, retire an accepted-to-buffer store once, continue driving buffered writes until dmemReady, and block younger memory operations while buffered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Distinguish load stalls and full-buffer/younger-memory stalls from isolated store backpressure so non-memory instructions can proceed behind a buffered store.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status between MEM and hazard control while keeping the nret=1 RVFI port set and channel-0 retirement order unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,42 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Add posted store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\n+  EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\n+  that means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\n+  work even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\n+  preserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\n+  while the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\n+  front-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\n+  decoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\n+  traffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry posted store buffer at the MEM stage. When a valid store\n+  reaches EX/MEM while io_dmemReady is low and the buffer is empty, capture its\n+  address, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI sideband, let the store\n+  retire exactly once through the normal channel-0 path, and allow subsequent\n+  non-memory instructions to keep flowing. The buffer continues driving the\n+  dmem write request until io_dmemReady accepts it.\n+\n+  To preserve precise in-order memory behavior, stall any later load or store\n+  while the buffer is occupied, and keep the existing full-pipeline dmem stall\n+  behavior when a load misses readiness or when a second store arrives before\n+  the buffer drains. This should recover cycles otherwise lost to isolated\n+  store backpressure under the apples-to-apples random stall model, with a\n+  smaller Fmax risk than fetch-side structural changes because the added state\n+  sits behind EX/MEM and does not affect branch redirect or PC selection.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Optionally add a compact store-buffer payload type or reuse existing EX/MEM fields needed to hold address, data, mask, and RVFI retirement metadata.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement the one-entry posted store buffer, retire an accepted-to-buffer store once, continue driving buffered writes until dmemReady, and block younger memory operations while buffered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Distinguish load stalls and full-buffer/younger-memory stalls from isolated store backpressure so non-memory instructions can proceed behind a buffered store.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status between MEM and hazard control while keeping the nret=1 RVFI port set and channel-0 retirement order unchanged.\"\n","additions":42,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778664239273,"end":1778664239276}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03739e5e5658ba2a016a04430db4c8819b9fd1abb782d6035b"}},"id":"prt_e20a5edee001MpWfqKdC01Vdlj","sessionID":"ses_1df5b277effeiZDCj1aKs4bhnS","messageID":"msg_e20a5d251001lxDsJgDOa1YHRN"}}
