{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778666687693,"sessionID":"ses_1df34bcc7ffeyhdId4u5zcI80E","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_w4IFOrGGAMKEulW0zqztquDb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Deepen posted store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The only recent structural improvement came from adding a one-entry posted store buffer, which lets an isolated store retire while its dmem write drains under random backpressure. That design still blocks when a second store arrives before the first buffered write is accepted, so short CoreMark store bursts can collapse back into full-pipeline stalls.\n+\n+  Front-end structural changes have repeatedly regressed by adding fetch-path or replay complexity. A slightly deeper store queue stays in the proven back-end decoupling direction and avoids changing branch, fetch, or RVFI top-level semantics.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the single posted-store entry in mem_stage with a two-entry ordered store buffer. When a valid non-misaligned store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, enqueue it if either slot is free and still let that store retire exactly once through channel 0; the oldest buffered entry continues to drive the dmem write port until accepted. Younger loads and stores must stall behind any buffered store to preserve precise memory ordering, but younger non-memory instructions can continue as they do today.\n+\n+  This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle in the random dmem-stall regime by absorbing back-to-back stores and store bursts, while adding only a small amount of MEM-stage control that is off the fragile IF next-PC path. RVFI mem_wmask/mem_wdata for the retiring store remain sourced from the current EX/MEM instruction, so order, trap, and single-retire invariants stay unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the one-entry posted store buffer with a two-entry FIFO, drain oldest-first to dmem, enqueue stalled stores when space is available, and keep RVFI store retirement data tied to the current MEM instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Interpret the store-buffer-full signal as FIFO-full and continue stalling younger memory operations while any buffered store is pending, without stalling younger non-memory instructions.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Deepen posted store buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The only recent structural improvement came from adding a one-entry posted store buffer, which lets an isolated store retire while its dmem write drains under random backpressure. That design still blocks when a second store arrives before the first buffered write is accepted, so short CoreMark store bursts can collapse back into full-pipeline stalls.\n+\n+  Front-end structural changes have repeatedly regressed by adding fetch-path or replay complexity. A slightly deeper store queue stays in the proven back-end decoupling direction and avoids changing branch, fetch, or RVFI top-level semantics.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the single posted-store entry in mem_stage with a two-entry ordered store buffer. When a valid non-misaligned store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, enqueue it if either slot is free and still let that store retire exactly once through channel 0; the oldest buffered entry continues to drive the dmem write port until accepted. Younger loads and stores must stall behind any buffered store to preserve precise memory ordering, but younger non-memory instructions can continue as they do today.\n+\n+  This should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle in the random dmem-stall regime by absorbing back-to-back stores and store bursts, while adding only a small amount of MEM-stage control that is off the fragile IF next-PC path. RVFI mem_wmask/mem_wdata for the retiring store remain sourced from the current EX/MEM instruction, so order, trap, and single-retire invariants stay unchanged.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the one-entry posted store buffer with a two-entry FIFO, drain oldest-first to dmem, enqueue stalled stores when space is available, and keep RVFI store retirement data tied to the current MEM instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Interpret the store-buffer-full signal as FIFO-full and continue stalling younger memory operations while any buffered store is pending, without stalling younger non-memory instructions.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-run