{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778668570010,"sessionID":"ses_1df17b387ffensrqPgf7FFuqJr","part":{"id":"prt_e20e88599001cuOTHD3mqbc7PN","messageID":"msg_e20e88267001iSEzFT47VNu4BR","sessionID":"ses_1df17b387ffensrqPgf7FFuqJr","snapshot":"58b422793b808ebf4390afca71e7e6382eb4408b","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778668592607,"sessionID":"ses_1df17b387ffensrqPgf7FFuqJr","part":{"id":"prt_e20e8dd5e001NqC2l3I2GG8oAv","messageID":"msg_e20e88267001iSEzFT47VNu4BR","sessionID":"ses_1df17b387ffensrqPgf7FFuqJr","type":"text","text":"The relevant history strongly disfavors more fetch/predictor retiming and deeper store queues. The least-overlapping structural opportunity is a true load-use bypass: let a dependent instruction enter EX behind a ready load and forward the MEM-stage load result directly instead of always inserting the one-cycle bubble.","time":{"start":1778668592478,"end":1778668592607},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0b525cd947542ff8016a0454305e24819892701390102f6c96","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778668619899,"sessionID":"ses_1df17b387ffensrqPgf7FFuqJr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_vqoOcM5wPmhLf84bRVJoqE3l","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Bypass ready load-use pairs\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\n+  a load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\n+  the data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\n+  array dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\n+  provide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\n+\n+  Prior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\n+  fetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\n+  loss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\n+  replay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated load-result forwarding path from mem_stage into ex_stage.\n+  When a load has advanced into EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is high, mem_stage\n+  already computes the sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally; expose\n+  that value plus a valid/rd indication and teach forward_unit/ex_stage to use\n+  it for the immediately following consumer instead of forwarding the load's\n+  address-valued alu_result. Change the load-use hazard so it stalls only when\n+  the producer load cannot deliver data, such as during dmem backpressure or\n+  when an older posted store forces memory ordering.\n+\n+  This preserves the nret=1 retirement boundary, RVFI operand reporting, and\n+  memory ordering because the dependent instruction still retires after the\n+  load and records the actual forwarded rs values. It should improve\n+  iterations/cycle on CoreMark's dependent load chains; the main risk is a\n+  modest Fmax hit from the new MEM-to-EX bypass mux, so the expected gain is\n+  positive but not as high as the earlier MDU structural split.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire MEM-stage load-forward valid, rd, and data signals into the forwarding network and EX operand muxes while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the already-computed sign/zero-extended load result as a same-cycle bypass source when a valid, aligned load has dmemReady.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Prioritize the ready load-result bypass over EX/MEM alu_result for source registers matching a load in MEM, while keeping existing EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding for other producers.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a third forwarding input/select for the MEM-stage load data so dependent ALU, branch, store-data, and JALR operands use the actual loaded value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Relax the fixed load-use bubble only when the EX/MEM load-result bypass will be available; retain stalls for dmem backpressure and ordered memory operations.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,44 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Bypass ready load-use pairs\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\n+  a load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\n+  the data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\n+  array dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\n+  provide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\n+\n+  Prior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\n+  fetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\n+  loss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\n+  replay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated load-result forwarding path from mem_stage into ex_stage.\n+  When a load has advanced into EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is high, mem_stage\n+  already computes the sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally; expose\n+  that value plus a valid/rd indication and teach forward_unit/ex_stage to use\n+  it for the immediately following consumer instead of forwarding the load's\n+  address-valued alu_result. Change the load-use hazard so it stalls only when\n+  the producer load cannot deliver data, such as during dmem backpressure or\n+  when an older posted store forces memory ordering.\n+\n+  This preserves the nret=1 retirement boundary, RVFI operand reporting, and\n+  memory ordering because the dependent instruction still retires after the\n+  load and records the actual forwarded rs values. It should improve\n+  iterations/cycle on CoreMark's dependent load chains; the main risk is a\n+  modest Fmax hit from the new MEM-to-EX bypass mux, so the expected gain is\n+  positive but not as high as the earlier MDU structural split.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire MEM-stage load-forward valid, rd, and data signals into the forwarding network and EX operand muxes while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the already-computed sign/zero-extended load result as a same-cycle bypass source when a valid, aligned load has dmemReady.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Prioritize the ready load-result bypass over EX/MEM alu_result for source registers matching a load in MEM, while keeping existing EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding for other producers.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a third forwarding input/select for the MEM-stage load data so dependent ALU, branch, store-data, and JALR operands use the actual loaded value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Relax the fixed load-use bubble only when the EX/MEM load-result bypass will be available; retain stalls for dmem backpressure and ordered memory operations.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,44 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Bypass ready load-use pairs\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\n+  a load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\n+  the data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\n+  array dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\n+  provide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\n+\n+  Prior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\n+  fetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\n+  loss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\n+  replay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a dedicated load-result forwarding path from mem_stage into ex_stage.\n+  When a load has advanced into EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is high, mem_stage\n+  already computes the sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally; expose\n+  that value plus a valid/rd indication and teach forward_unit/ex_stage to use\n+  it for the immediately following consumer instead of forwarding the load's\n+  address-valued alu_result. Change the load-use hazard so it stalls only when\n+  the producer load cannot deliver data, such as during dmem backpressure or\n+  when an older posted store forces memory ordering.\n+\n+  This preserves the nret=1 retirement boundary, RVFI operand reporting, and\n+  memory ordering because the dependent instruction still retires after the\n+  load and records the actual forwarded rs values. It should improve\n+  iterations/cycle on CoreMark's dependent load chains; the main risk is a\n+  modest Fmax hit from the new MEM-to-EX bypass mux, so the expected gain is\n+  positive but not as high as the earlier MDU structural split.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire MEM-stage load-forward valid, rd, and data signals into the forwarding network and EX operand muxes while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the already-computed sign/zero-extended load result as a same-cycle bypass source when a valid, aligned load has dmemReady.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Prioritize the ready load-result bypass over EX/MEM alu_result for source registers matching a load in MEM, while keeping existing EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding for other producers.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a third forwarding input/select for the MEM-stage load data so dependent ALU, branch, store-data, and JALR operands use the actual loaded value.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Relax the fixed load-use bubble only when the EX/MEM load-result bypass will be available; retain stalls for dmem backpressure and ordered memory operations.\"\n","additions":44,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778668619895,"end":1778668619898}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b525cd947542ff8016a04543083808198937aec47b507711f"}},"id":"prt_e20e8dde0001eUdXuAzCYMmAHF","sessionID":"ses_1df17b387ffensrqPgf7FFuqJr","messageID":"msg_e20e88267001iSEzFT47VNu4BR"}}
