{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778670647510,"sessionID":"ses_1def7f214ffeyFirOaJREhnwg4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_9FdIUbxRmBLkTNp7o0a8t7U5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r1s0 (improvement, +11.81%): Avoid resetting RV32I regfile backing arrays when x0 is enforced by read/write gating, because reset fanout can block LUTRAM-friendly inference and hurt FPGA Fmax without improving initialized CoreMark code.\n2: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (regression, -30.56%): ID-stage branch resolution needs real EX/MEM operand bypasses to help CoreMark counted loops; conservatively disabling early redirects on any in-flight producer mostly preserves the EX penalty while adding front-end control/comparison cost.\n3: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (broken, n/a): Fetch prediction cannot simply suppress the existing EX redirect on correctly predicted branches; the speculative IF/ID path must still preserve RVFI branch pc_wdata/pc_fwd semantics and flush only proven wrong-path instructions.\n4: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-use source qualification should stay in the stall path unless RVFI source reporting is updated coherently; zeroing ID-stage rs*_addr/rs*_rdata for “unused” operands can break riscv-formal's reg check even when the datapath dependency is false.\n5: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r2s1 (improvement, +12.85%): Moving rare RV32M multiply/divide operations into a stalling multicycle MDU can improve Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark's hot RV32I-heavy EX path benefits more from removing multiplier/divider cones than it loses to occasional M-op latency.\n6: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 (regression, +3.30%): Decode-light IF prediction for JALs and backward branches can lose overall fitness when immediate extraction and opcode checks sit directly on the fetch-to-next-PC path, so CoreMark loop flush savings must outweigh added front-end critical-path cost.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (improvement, +11.43%): Pruning unused pipeline metadata such as ctrl_t.is_lui and flopped EX/MEM branch redirect fields can materially improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax because post-MDU fitness is limited by hot-stage register width and routing, not CPI.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -9.18%): A one-entry IF skid buffer can regress CoreMark when PC-hold already preserves fetch state across back-end stalls, because the added IF/ID replay muxing and buffer-valid hazard feedback cost more Fmax than they save in random imem stalls.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -3.40%): Even a return-only RAS predictor can regress CoreMark when JALR return savings are outweighed by fetch next-PC critical-path work from return-shape decode, stack-top muxing, and prediction metadata plumbing.\n10: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (regression, -0.26%): Pruning a redundant writeback select bit is not automatically helpful when it makes `mem_read` drive both memory control and the WB result mux, because extra load-control fanout can offset narrower pipeline registers.\n11: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): A registered IF/ID boundary needs a precise valid/ready replay contract; clearing IF/ID on `imem_stall` while holding the PC can lose the in-flight instruction stream and break CoreMark cosim.\n12: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -4.84%): A single-entry last-target predictor avoids IF immediate decode but still regresses when its PC comparator, next-PC muxing, and predicted_next_pc pipeline metadata add more fetch/control-path cost than CoreMark loop redirect savings recover.\n13: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -17.19%): Splitting `ctrl_t` into narrower EX/MEM and MEM/WB records can regress badly if it adds repacking logic and trap-control muxing on hot stage boundaries; downstream metadata pruning only pays when it removes routing without creating new control cones.\n14: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r5s1 (improvement, +1.97%): A one-entry posted store buffer helps random dmem-stall CoreMark runs by letting isolated stores retire and drain later while stalling younger memory ops, adding useful back-end decoupling without touching the fragile fetch next-PC path.\n15: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -30.80%): Moving target prediction from IF to ID still regresses when the learned table, tag/counter read, pred_pc_next metadata, and EX suppression/repair logic add more control-path cost than CoreMark recovers from saving only one taken-branch bubble.\n16: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -17.33%): Partially resetting only valid/control fields inside wide pipeline structs can worsen Tang Nano 20K fitness by creating mixed reset/control sets and scattered muxing, so reset-fanout pruning is safer on isolated arrays than on tightly packed stage registers.\n17: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (placement_failed, n/a): Deepening the posted store buffer from one entry to a shifting two-entry FIFO can exceed Tang Nano 20K placement/routing limits; back-end decoupling only stays cheap while store-buffer control and data movement remain minimal.\n18: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (regression, -3.18%): Direction-only not-taken confidence prediction still regresses when the BHT tag/counter read, update path, and predicted_not_taken metadata add ID/EX control cost without changing the already-cheap pc+4 fetch path.\n19: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -0.03%): Shortening isolated MDU multiply latency from two cycles to one is effectively noise on CoreMark, suggesting post-MDU fitness is dominated by hot RV32I timing/routing rather than occasional MUL hold cycles.\n20: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.12%): MEM-to-EX load-result bypassing can regress CoreMark when the same-cycle dmem_ready/load_data path adds forwarding mux and hazard-control delay to hot ALU operands, so eliminating one load-use bubble is not worth lengthening the common EX path.\n21: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r7s2 (regression, -29.17%): Even JAL-only ID-stage prediction can badly regress when it adds a second redirect source to IF PC update/flush priority plus `pred_jal` EX suppression metadata; saving one direct-jump bubble is not worth lengthening the fragile fetch control path.\n22: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r8s0 (regression, -0.10%): Replacing SV DIV/REM operators with an iterative restoring divider was effectively neutral/regressive, suggesting post-MDU CoreMark fitness is not limited by rare division hardware and can be offset by added divider state/control routing.\n23: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r8s1 (regression, -25.51%): Precomputing forwarding selects in ID only helps if EX fully trusts them; keeping fallback EX/MEM and MEM/WB rd comparisons preserves the hot operand-forwarding cone while adding ID/EX register width and control routing.\n\n(End of file - total 23 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r1s0 (improvement, +11.81%): Avoid resetting RV32I regfile backing arrays when x0 is enforced by read/write gating, because reset fanout can block LUTRAM-friendly inference and hurt FPGA Fmax without improving initialized CoreMark code.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r1s1 (regression, -30.56%): ID-stage branch resolution needs real EX/MEM operand bypasses to help CoreMark counted loops; conservatively disabling early redirects on any in-flight producer mostly preserves the EX penalty while adding front-end control/comparison cost.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r1s2 (broken, n/a): Fetch prediction cannot simply suppress the existing EX redirect on correctly predicted branches; the speculative IF/ID path must still preserve RVFI branch pc_wdata/pc_fwd semantics and flush only proven wrong-path instructions.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Load-use source qualification should stay in the stall path unless RVFI source reporting is updated coherently; zeroing ID-stage rs*_addr/rs*_rdata for “unused” operands can break riscv-formal's reg check even when the datapath dependency is false.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r2s1 (improvement, +12.85%): Moving rare RV32M multiply/divide operations into a stalling multicycle MDU can improve Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark's hot RV32I-heavy EX path benefits more from removing multiplier/divider cones than it loses to occasional M-op latency.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r2s2 (regression, +3.30%): Decode-light IF prediction for JALs and backward branches can lose overall fitness when immediate extraction and opcode checks sit directly on the fetch-to-next-PC path, so CoreMark loop flush savings must outweigh added front-end critical-path cost.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (improvement, +11.43%): Pruning unused pipeline metadata such as ctrl_t.is_lui and flopped EX/MEM branch redirect fields can materially improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax because post-MDU fitness is limited by hot-stage register width and routing, not CPI.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -9.18%): A one-entry IF skid buffer can regress CoreMark when PC-hold already preserves fetch state across back-end stalls, because the added IF/ID replay muxing and buffer-valid hazard feedback cost more Fmax than they save in random imem stalls.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -3.40%): Even a return-only RAS predictor can regress CoreMark when JALR return savings are outweighed by fetch next-PC critical-path work from return-shape decode, stack-top muxing, and prediction metadata plumbing.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (regression, -0.26%): Pruning a redundant writeback select bit is not automatically helpful when it makes `mem_read` drive both memory control and the WB result mux, because extra load-control fanout can offset narrower pipeline registers.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): A registered IF/ID boundary needs a precise valid/ready replay contract; clearing IF/ID on `imem_stall` while holding the PC can lose the in-flight instruction stream and break CoreMark cosim.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -4.84%): A single-entry last-target predictor avoids IF immediate decode but still regresses when its PC comparator, next-PC muxing, and predicted_next_pc pipeline metadata add more fetch/control-path cost than CoreMark loop redirect savings recover.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -17.19%): Splitting `ctrl_t` into narrower EX/MEM and MEM/WB records can regress badly if it adds repacking logic and trap-control muxing on hot stage boundaries; downstream metadata pruning only pays when it removes routing without creating new control cones.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r5s1 (improvement, +1.97%): A one-entry posted store buffer helps random dmem-stall CoreMark runs by letting isolated stores retire and drain later while stalling younger memory ops, adding useful back-end decoupling without touching the fragile fetch next-PC path.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -30.80%): Moving target prediction from IF to ID still regresses when the learned table, tag/counter read, pred_pc_next metadata, and EX suppression/repair logic add more control-path cost than CoreMark recovers from saving only one taken-branch bubble.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -17.33%): Partially resetting only valid/control fields inside wide pipeline structs can worsen Tang Nano 20K fitness by creating mixed reset/control sets and scattered muxing, so reset-fanout pruning is safer on isolated arrays than on tightly packed stage registers.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (placement_failed, n/a): Deepening the posted store buffer from one entry to a shifting two-entry FIFO can exceed Tang Nano 20K placement/routing limits; back-end decoupling only stays cheap while store-buffer control and data movement remain minimal.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (regression, -3.18%): Direction-only not-taken confidence prediction still regresses when the BHT tag/counter read, update path, and predicted_not_taken metadata add ID/EX control cost without changing the already-cheap pc+4 fetch path.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -0.03%): Shortening isolated MDU multiply latency from two cycles to one is effectively noise on CoreMark, suggesting post-MDU fitness is dominated by hot RV32I timing/routing rather than occasional MUL hold cycles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -13.12%): MEM-to-EX load-result bypassing can regress CoreMark when the same-cycle dmem_ready/load_data path adds forwarding mux and hazard-control delay to hot ALU operands, so eliminating one load-use bubble is not worth lengthening the common EX path.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778670647488,"end":1778670647509}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_01c85248fc82b3d0016a045c37579881999bf9306a0bd64d91"}},"id":"prt_e210838ac001npnjzqUa171Cm4","sessionID":"ses_1def7f214ffeyFirOaJREhnwg4","messageID":"msg_e21080e220019jnWsmecQOPb9t"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778670647513,"sessionID":"ses_1def7f214ffeyFirOaJREhnwg4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_RDXNXDrhmetdpZ3Sd7hzih6I","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\"category\"\\s*:\\s*\"structural\"|category: structural|structural","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 8 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Resolve branches in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every branch and jump in EX, so each\\ntaken redirect flushes two younger instructions. CoreMark spends many cycles\\nin tight counted loops and function-call-heavy list/state code, making taken\\ncontrol transfers a direct CPI cost. Reducing the redirect penalty by one\\nstage should improve iterations per cycle without changing the nret=1 RVFI\\ncontract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves every branch and jump in EX, so each\\ntaken redirect flushes two younger instructions. CoreMark spends many cycles\\nin tight counted loops and function-call-heavy list/state code, making taken\\ncontrol transfers a direct CPI cost. Reducing the redirect penalty by one\\nstage should improve iterations per cycle without changing the nret=1 RVFI\\ncontract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an ID-stage early redirect path for conditional branches, JAL, and JALR\\nwhen their operands are already available from the regfile or safe same-cycle\\nbypasses. The ID stage can compute immediates, branch comparisons, and jump\\ntargets one cycle earlier than EX; when it redirects, IF emits a bubble and\\nID/EX captures a bubble so the control-transfer instruction still retires\\nthrough the normal pipeline with correct RVFI pc_wdata. Cases needing an\\nunavailable producer, especially load-use and EX/MEM load results, fall back\\nto the existing EX resolution path for correctness.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire an early ID redirect signal into IF and hazard control while preserving the existing EX redirect fallback and single-channel RVFI retirement.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute branch and jump targets in ID, compare available operands with WB bypassing, emit an early redirect, and carry the resolved pc_next metadat...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Move M extension to multicycle unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\\nremainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\\nCoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\\nsynthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\\nEX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\\noperations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\\na favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage instantiates three 64-bit multipliers plus divider and\\nremainder operators inside the always-active combinational ALU. Even when\\nCoreMark is executing ordinary integer, branch, and address-generation ops,\\nsynthesis must carry that large structural cone through the ALU module and\\nEX-stage muxing, which is a likely Fmax limiter on the Tang Nano 20K.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loops use mostly RV32I control, load/store, and simple ALU\\noperations, so paying extra cycles only on rare RV32M instructions should be\\na favorable trade if the common EX path becomes smaller and faster.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split RV32M operations out of the combinational ALU into a dedicated\\nmulticycle mdu module, leaving alu.sv as a compact single-cycle RV32I datapath\\nfor add/sub/logic/compare/shift/LUI/address generation. The EX stage detects\\nALU_MUL* and ALU_DIV/REM* operations, launches the MDU, and stalls the front\\nhalf of the pipeline until the result is available, then writes the result\\ninto the normal EX/MEM register so RVFI ordering and single-retire semantics\\nstay unchanged.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should raise Fmax by removing the multiplier and\\ndivider hardware from the common EX critical path. The CPI loss should b...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Add one-entry fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\\nthe PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\\nrandom instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\\nthis tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\\ncycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\\nfetched word.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\\nfront-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\\nthe fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\\nit should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\\nthe existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end presents imem_data directly into decode and only holds\\nthe PC when the back half of the pipeline stalls. Under the benchmark's\\nrandom instruction stalls plus occasional load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls,\\nthis tightly couples fetch availability to decode acceptance and can waste\\ncycles where the instruction bus is ready but ID/EX cannot yet consume the\\nfetched word.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts at earlier branch resolution and predictor-like\\nfront-end changes regressed or broke because they added control-path work on\\nthe fetch next-PC path. A tiny skid buffer is a narrower structural change:\\nit should improve useful instruction delivery during stalls while preserving\\nthe existing EX-stage authoritative redirect and RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry IF/ID fetch skid buffer in the front end. When imemReady is\\nhigh but decode is stalled by load-use, dmem backpressure, or an MDU busy\\nperiod, capture the current fetched instruction and PC instead of emitting a\\nbubble or requiring the instruction bus to be ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Register the IF ID boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID pipeline register: imem_data, PC,\\ndecode, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and the ID/EX\\ncapture all sit in one cycle. After the successful MDU split and metadata\\npruning, the remaining Tang Nano 20K fitness is likely limited by routing and\\nlong stage boundaries rather than by CoreMark CPI alone.\\n\\nPrior structural and predictor attempts that added front-end speculation or\\nreplay state regressed because they put new work on the fetch next-PC path.\\nA plain IF/ID register is a narrower structural retiming that does not try to\\npredict control flow; it simply cuts the fetch-to-decode path and lets the PC\\nand instruction memory interface settle before decode consumes the word.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID pipeline register: imem_data, PC,\\ndecode, immediate generation, register-file address selection, and the ID/EX\\ncapture all sit in one cycle. After the successful MDU split and metadata\\npruning, the remaining Tang Nano 20K fitness is likely limited by routing and\\nlong stage boundaries rather than by CoreMark CPI alone.\\n\\nPrior structural and predictor attempts that added front-end speculation or\\nreplay state regressed because they put new work on the fetch next-PC path.\\nA plain IF/ID register is a narrower structural retiming that does not try to\\npredict control flow; it simply cuts the fetch-to-decode path and lets the PC\\nand instruction memory interface settle before decode consumes the word.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the current combinational IF/ID bundle into a registered pipeline\\nboundary owned by if_stage. The IF stage should capture pc, instr, and valid\\nwhen imemReady is high and decode can advance; hold the registered bundle\\nduring load-use, dmem, and MDU stalls; and flush it on redirects or invalid\\ninstruction-fetch cycles....\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Add posted store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\\nEX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\\nthat means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\\nwork even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\\npreserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\\nwhile the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\\nfront-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\\ndecoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\\ntraffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes the entire front half whenever a store sits in\\nEX/MEM and io_dmemReady is low. In the benchmark's random dmem-stall mode,\\nthat means a store with no register result can block unrelated following ALU\\nwork even though in-order retirement only requires the store request to be\\npreserved and later memory operations to remain ordered.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that touched fetch replay or prediction regressed,\\nwhile the successful changes reduced hot-path pressure without changing the\\nfront-end next-PC path. A tiny posted store buffer is a back-end structural\\ndecoupling point: it targets random dmem backpressure and CoreMark's store\\ntraffic without adding IF critical-path logic.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry posted store buffer at the MEM stage. When a valid store\\nreaches EX/MEM while io_dmemReady is low and the buffer is empty, capture its\\naddress, replicated write data, byte mask, and RVFI sideband, let the store\\nretire exactly once through the normal channel-0 path, and allow subsequent\\nnon-memory instructions to keep flowing. The buffer continues driving the\\ndmem write r...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Deepen posted store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The only recent structural improvement came from adding a one-entry posted store buffer, which lets an isolated store retire while its dmem write drains under random backpressure. That design still blocks when a second store arrives before the first buffered write is accepted, so short CoreMark store bursts can collapse back into full-pipeline stalls.\\n\\nFront-end structural changes have repeatedly regressed by adding fetch-path or replay complexity. A slightly deeper store queue stays in the proven back-end decoupling direction and avoids changing branch, fetch, or RVFI top-level semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only recent structural improvement came from adding a one-entry posted store buffer, which lets an isolated store retire while its dmem write drains under random backpressure. That design still blocks when a second store arrives before the first buffered write is accepted, so short CoreMark store bursts can collapse back into full-pipeline stalls.\\n\\nFront-end structural changes have repeatedly regressed by adding fetch-path or replay complexity. A slightly deeper store queue stays in the proven back-end decoupling direction and avoids changing branch, fetch, or RVFI top-level semantics.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the single posted-store entry in mem_stage with a two-entry ordered store buffer. When a valid non-misaligned store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, enqueue it if either slot is free and still let that store retire exactly once through channel 0; the oldest buffered entry continues to drive the dmem write port until accepted. Younger loads and stores must stall behind any buffered store to preserve precise memory ordering, but younger non-memory instructions can continue as they do today.\\n\\nThis should improve CoreMark iterations/cycle in the random dmem-stall regime by absorbing back-to-back stores and store bursts, w...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Bypass ready load-use pairs\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\\na load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\\nthe data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\\narray dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\\nprovide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\\nfetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\\nloss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\\nreplay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline still pays a fixed one-cycle bubble whenever\\na load in EX is followed by an instruction that consumes its rd, even when\\nthe data-memory port is ready the next cycle. CoreMark has many pointer and\\narray dependent load-use pairs, and the benchmark's random dmem stalls already\\nprovide the necessary full-pipeline hold when the load data is not available.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from back-end decoupling and keeping the fragile\\nfetch path unchanged. A MEM-to-EX load-result bypass targets a direct CPI\\nloss in the back half of the pipeline without adding branch prediction,\\nreplay buffering, or deeper store-queue placement pressure.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated load-result forwarding path from mem_stage into ex_stage.\\nWhen a load has advanced into EX/MEM and io_dmemReady is high, mem_stage\\nalready computes the sign/zero-extended load_data combinationally; expose\\nthat value plus a valid/rd indication and teach forward_unit/ex_stage to use\\nit for the immediately following consumer instead of forwarding the load's\\naddress-valued alu_result. Change the load-use hazard so it stalls only when\\nthe producer load cannot...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute forwarding selects in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage resolves both operand-forwarding mux selects with two\\n5-bit destination comparisons against EX/MEM and MEM/WB immediately before\\nthe ALU, branch comparator, MDU launch, and EX/MEM register boundary. After\\nthe successful MDU split, Tang Nano 20K fitness appears dominated by hot\\nRV32I timing and routing rather than rare long-latency M operations.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from removing common-path pressure, while attempts\\nto add front-end prediction, replay, or deeper queues regressed. Moving the\\nforwarding compare work one stage earlier is a structural retiming that keeps\\nfetch, branch resolution, memory ordering, and the nret=1 RVFI contract\\nunchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage resolves both operand-forwarding mux selects with two\\n5-bit destination comparisons against EX/MEM and MEM/WB immediately before\\nthe ALU, branch comparator, MDU launch, and EX/MEM register boundary. After\\nthe successful MDU split, Tang Nano 20K fitness appears dominated by hot\\nRV32I timing and routing rather than rare long-latency M operations.\\n\\nPrior structural wins came from removing common-path pressure, while attempts\\nto add front-end prediction, replay, or deeper queues regressed. Moving the\\nforwarding compare work one stage earlier is a structural retiming that keeps\\nfetch, branch resolution, memory ordering, and the nret=1 RVFI contract\\nunchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Compute the EX operand forwarding selects while the consumer instruction is\\nstill in ID, comparing IF/ID rs1/rs2 against the instruction currently in EX\\nand the instruction currently in MEM. Latch those two 2-bit selects into the\\nID/EX payload, then make ex_stage use the precomputed selects directly for\\nits rs1/rs2 muxes.\\n\\nThis removes forward_unit's register-number comparator cone from the EX-stage\\nALU/branch critical path and...","metadata":{"matches":8,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\"\\s*:\\s*\"structural\"|category: structural|structural","time":{"start":1778670647494,"end":1778670647512}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_01c85248fc82b3d0016a045c3757ac81998bbcc9d741d01b39"}},"id":"prt_e210838c2001PyHcwriPbYgioS","sessionID":"ses_1def7f214ffeyFirOaJREhnwg4","messageID":"msg_e21080e220019jnWsmecQOPb9t"}}
