{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778657283699,"sessionID":"ses_1dfc49ea4ffeSK9JEwsQSAHpsJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_NWuPQRU3koBnoCFjla7lNur8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r1s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r1s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\n2: title: \"Add tiny BTB and BHT branch predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current five-stage pipeline always fetches pc+4 and resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken control-flow instruction pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark contains tight loops and repeated call/return style control flow where even a very small FPGA-friendly predictor should learn the hot backedges and reduce bubbles. A predictor is especially attractive under the random instruction-stall workload because it improves useful fetch placement without adding memory-system complexity.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with 2-bit saturating direction counters in the IF stage. The IF stage predicts taken when the PC tag hits and the BHT counter is weak/strong taken, uses the cached target as next_pc, and carries predicted_pc/predicted_taken metadata down the pipeline. EX compares the actual resolved next PC against the prediction, redirects only on mispredict, and updates the BTB/BHT for branches and jumps. This should preserve correctness through the existing redirect/flush machinery while converting most steady-state CoreMark loop backedges from taken-branch flushes into correctly predicted fetches.\n8: expected_impact:\n9:   fitness_delta_pct: 8\n10:   confidence: medium\n11: changes:\n12:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n13:     description: \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with predicted_taken and predicted_pc metadata used for EX-stage mispredict detection.\"\n14:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n15:     description: \"Add a tiny direct-mapped BTB plus 2-bit BHT, use it to choose next_pc, and expose update inputs from EX for resolved branches and jumps.\"\n16:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n17:     description: \"Compare predicted next PC with the resolved branch/jump/fall-through PC, assert redirect only on mispredict, and emit predictor update information.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n19:     description: \"Wire predictor metadata and update signals between IF and EX while preserving the existing single-retire RVFI and memory IO contract.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n21:     description: \"Treat EX mispredict redirects like the existing redirect flush path so wrong-path IF/ID and ID/EX instructions are killed without changing load-use or dmem-stall behavior.\"\n\n(End of file - total 21 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-003-r1s2\ntitle: \"Add tiny BTB and BHT branch predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current five-stage pipeline always fetches pc+4 and resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken control-flow instruction pays a two-instruction wrong-path flush. CoreMark contains tight loops and repeated call/return style control flow where even a very small FPGA-friendly predictor should learn the hot backedges and reduce bubbles. A predictor is especially attractive under the random instruction-stall workload because it improves useful fetch placement without adding memory-system complexity.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a small direct-mapped branch target buffer with 2-bit saturating direction counters in the IF stage. The IF stage predicts taken when the PC tag hits and the BHT counter is weak/strong taken, uses the cached target as next_pc, and carries predicted_pc/predicted_taken metadata down the pipeline. EX compares the actual resolved next PC against the prediction, redirects only on mispredict, and updates the BTB/BHT for branches and jumps. This should preserve correctness through the existing redirect/flush machinery while converting most steady-state CoreMark loop backedges from taken-branch flushes into correctly predicted fetches.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles with predicted_taken and predicted_pc metadata used for EX-stage mispredict detection.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add a tiny direct-mapped BTB plus 2-bit BHT, use it to choose next_pc, and expose update inputs from EX for resolved branches and jumps.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compare predicted next PC with the resolved branch/jump/fall-through PC, assert redirect only on mispredict, and emit predictor update information.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire predictor metadata and update signals between IF and EX while preserving the existing single-retire RVFI and memory IO contract.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r1s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778657283688,"end":1778657283698}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06ac906c4b02ba7b016a04280393b0819aab3432f129715678"}},"id":"prt_e203c4e67001aNTmT6tIpF3eRM","sessionID":"ses_1dfc49ea4ffeSK9JEwsQSAHpsJ","messageID":"msg_e203c136c001eiO00p3jdbOTvN"}}
