{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778663267391,"sessionID":"ses_1df6a01e0ffedsnHOJ3sIhcY6e","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_Au6Dg6MHI5659sl97fXqLVno","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Single-entry loop target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts show that broad IF-stage decode, BTB/BHT state, and return-shape logic can cost more Tang Nano 20K Fmax than they recover in CPI. CoreMark still pays a two-instruction redirect penalty on hot taken loop backedges, so the best remaining predictor angle is one that learns those targets without re-decoding immediates on the fetch critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry last-taken control-flow target predictor. EX remains the authoritative branch/jump resolver and, whenever a valid taken branch or direct jump retires through the existing redirect path, records the resolved PC and target in two small registers. IF predicts only when the current PC equals that registered PC, using the registered target as next_pc; all other fetches stay on the current pc+4 path.\n+\n+  Carry predicted-next-PC metadata with each instruction so EX can compare the actual resolved next PC against the predicted one and only flush on mismatch. This targets steady-state counted loops with much less fetch-path logic than the prior static predictor or BTB/BHT, while preserving RVFI pc_wdata/order semantics and using the existing redirect machinery for recovery.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate speculation without changing the nret=1 RVFI interface.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add one registered last-taken PC/target lookup input path and select predicted target only on a simple PC equality hit; keep pc+4 as the default.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Compare predicted next PC against the resolved branch/jump next PC, request redirect only on mismatch, and expose taken PC/target updates for the predictor.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire predictor update and predicted-next-PC signals between IF and EX while preserving existing stall, flush, and RVFI retirement behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Single-entry loop target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts show that broad IF-stage decode, BTB/BHT state, and return-shape logic can cost more Tang Nano 20K Fmax than they recover in CPI. CoreMark still pays a two-instruction redirect penalty on hot taken loop backedges, so the best remaining predictor angle is one that learns those targets without re-decoding immediates on the fetch critical path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry last-taken control-flow target predictor. EX remains the authoritative branch/jump resolver and, whenever a valid taken branch or direct jump retires through the existing redirect path, records the resolved PC and target in