{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778676714842,"sessionID":"ses_1de9ecc0cffe0G79S3mVPj20U0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_yzbaXitqVYlRMdBS3nBJFjxn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n+## Store Buffer Drain Refill\n+\n+Changed `mem_stage.sv` so the existing one-entry posted store buffer can drain an older buffered store while capturing a younger aligned store from EX/MEM in the same cycle. The buffered store continues to own the dmem port for that cycle; the younger store retires through MEM/WB once and replaces the buffer entry for a later drain.\n+\n+Changed `hazard_unit.sv` so a full store buffer still blocks younger loads, and still blocks younger stores while dmem is not ready, but no longer stalls a younger store when the buffered store is accepted in the same cycle. Non-memory instructions keep the previous behavior and may retire behind a draining or stalled buffered store.\n+\n+No top-level IO or `nret: 1` RVFI contract changes were made. No deviations from the proposed approach.\n+\n+Concern: this preserves the existing posted-store RVFI model, where store retirement can precede the physical dmem write. Younger loads remain blocked behind buffered stores to preserve visible memory ordering.\n+\n+Local checks:\n+- Verilator lint: pass (`verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv +incdir+cores/bench/rtl cores/bench/rtl/*.sv`)\n+- Formal: pass (`RTL_DIR=cores/bench/rtl CORE_NAME=bench bash formal/run_all.sh`, 53 passed / 0 failed)\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/implementation_notes.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,13 @@\n+## Store Buffer Drain Refill\n+\n+Changed `mem_stage.sv` so the existing one-entry posted store buffer can drain an older buffered store while capturing a younger aligned store from EX/MEM in the same cycle. The buffered store continues to own the dmem port for that cycle; the younger store retires through MEM/WB once and replaces the buffer entry for a later drain.\n+\n+Changed `hazard_unit.sv` so a full store buffer still blocks younger loads, and still blocks younger stores while dmem is not ready, but no longer stalls a younger store when the buffered store is accepted in the same cycle. Non-memory instructions keep the previous behavior and may retire behind a draining or stalled buffered store.\n+\n+No top-level IO or `nret: 1` RVFI contract changes were made. No deviations from the proposed approach.\n+\n+Concern: this preserves the existing posted-store RVFI model, where store retirement can precede the physical dmem write. Younger loads remain blocked behind buffered stores to preserve visible memory ordering.\n+\n+Local checks:\n+- Verilator lint: pass (`verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv +incdir+cores/bench/rtl cores/bench/rtl/*.sv`)\n+- Formal: pass (`RTL_DIR=cores/bench/rtl CORE_NAME=bench bash formal/run_all.sh`, 53 passed / 0 failed)\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md","relativePath":"cores/bench/implementation_notes.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,13 @@\n+## Store Buffer Drain Refill\n+\n+Changed `mem_stage.sv` so the existing one-entry posted store buffer can drain an older buffered store while capturing a younger aligned store from EX/MEM in the same cycle. The buffered store continues to own the dmem port for that cycle; the younger store retires through MEM/WB once and replaces the buffer entry for a later drain.\n+\n+Changed `hazard_unit.sv` so a full store buffer still blocks younger loads, and still blocks younger stores while dmem is not ready, but no longer stalls a younger store when the buffered store is accepted in the same cycle. Non-memory instructions keep the previous behavior and may retire behind a draining or stalled buffered store.\n+\n+No top-level IO or `nret: 1` RVFI contract changes were made. No deviations from the proposed approach.\n+\n+Concern: this preserves the existing posted-store RVFI model, where store retirement can precede the physical dmem write. Younger loads remain blocked behind buffered stores to preserve visible memory ordering.\n+\n+Local checks:\n+- Verilator lint: pass (`verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv +incdir+cores/bench/rtl cores/bench/rtl/*.sv`)\n+- Formal: pass (`RTL_DIR=cores/bench/rtl CORE_NAME=bench bash formal/run_all.sh`, 53 passed / 0 failed)\n","additions":13,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/implementation_notes.md","time":{"start":1778676714837,"end":1778676714841}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_092e952e0f7ffbd0016a0473df8c1c819