{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778667141342,"sessionID":"ses_1df341841ffeOPKGMndGK4Y49c","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_5Bo9Kc7SUPtDv3qcGriOyfIJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_medium-rep1/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260513-002-r6s1/cores/bench/implementation_notes.md\n+## Deepen posted store buffer\n+\n+Changed `rtl/mem_stage.sv` from a one-entry posted store buffer to a two-entry ordered FIFO. The oldest buffered store owns the dmem write port until `dmem_ready`; current MEM-stage stores enqueue behind it when the bus is stalled or already occupied, and still retire once through the normal MEM/WB RVFI path.\n+\n+Added separate `store_buffer_pending` and `store_buffer_full` status signals through `rtl/core.sv` into `rtl/hazard_unit.sv`. Loads now stall behind any pending older buffered store, while stores stall only when the FIFO is full. Non-memory instructions are not stalled by pending buffered stores.\n+\n+No intentional deviations from the hypothesis. The one conservative behavior is that a store seeing a full FIFO still stalls for that cycle even if the oldest entry drains in the same cycle; this keeps the hazard interface simple and preserves correctness, with only a small missed opportunity in the full-and-ready corner.\n+\n+Concerns: the FIFO adds a small amount of MEM-stage control and storage. RVFI store `mem_wmask` and `mem_wdata` remain sourced from the current EX/MEM instruction, not replayed from the buffer.\n+\n+Local verification:\n+- `verilator --lint-only -Wall -Wno-MULTITOP -sv +incdir+cores/bench/rtl cores/bench/rtl/*.sv`: pass\n+- `RTL_DIR=cores/bench/rtl CORE_NAME=bench bash formal/run_all.sh`: pass, 53 passed / 0 failed\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/implementation_notes.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/